{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780727708801,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba47c80001f95kZPy0M3Q2BU","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","snapshot":"b4f86407878a2060bff75674a9d7e8d8a0d5ee9d","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780727723666,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba481b90011xSyCDW7vPkkRs","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","type":"text","text":"The implementation confirms governance is not just schema: MCP auth resolves tenant/agent/readable-tenants/capabilities into context vars, search narrows low-trust agents to their fleet, and cross-tenant reads are audited. I’m reading the service-level gates and memory model for final citations.","time":{"start":1780727710137,"end":1780727723663},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bf9e1e3c81919f60d4ae2fe7b336","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723704,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1bpywEqWtSY3CPUyv9hmk7SQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement.\n2: \n3: Shared by the MCP handlers in ``core_api.mcp_server`` and the REST routes\n4: under ``core_api.routes`` so both surfaces gate on the same rule without\n5: reaching into each other's private symbols.\n6: \n7: ``require_trust`` returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass and\n8: ``(trust, not_found, error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is a typed flag\n9: for the \"agent row is missing\" case so callers can distinguish \"unknown\n10: id\" from \"known id with insufficient trust\" without parsing the error\n11: string. The error string carries the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` constant so\n12: the MCP handler convention stays in one place; ``parse_trust_error``\n13: strips that prefix so REST routes can surface the bare detail through\n14: an ``HTTPException``.\n15: \n16: When the agent row is missing (``not_found=True``), the gate falls back\n17: to ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` rather than treating the row's absence as a\n18: permission failure: API-key admission already proved authorization, so\n19: a fresh agent that hasn't yet been materialised by a write must still\n20: be allowed to use any tool the tenant's default policy permits. Code\n21: paths that need the row to exist (per-agent tuning, audit attribution)\n22: should call ``get_or_create_agent`` explicitly — the soft-pass here\n23: applies only to the gate decision.\n24: \"\"\"\n25: \n26: from __future__ import annotations\n27: \n28: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n29: \n30: from core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\n31: \n32: # Keep the prefix in one place so ``parse_trust_error`` and ``require_trust``\n33: # can't drift if someone edits one. ``str.removeprefix`` is a no-op when the\n34: # prefix isn't present, so parse_trust_error stays robust against future\n35: # error strings that happen not to start with it.\n36: _MCP_ERROR_PREFIX = \"Error (403): \"\n37: \n38: \n39: async def require_trust(\n40:     db: AsyncSession,\n41:     tenant_id: str,\n42:     agent_id: str,\n43:     min_level: int,\n44: ) -> tuple[int, bool, str | None]:\n45:     \"\"\"Look up the agent's trust level and gate on ``min_level``.\n46: \n47:     Returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass, ``(trust, not_found,\n48:     error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is ``True`` when no agent row\n49:     exists for ``(tenant_id, agent_id)``; in that case the effective\n50:     trust used for the gate decision is ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` (the\n51:     same level a freshly-registered agent receives). Error format\n52:     matches the wider MCP handler convention of ``\"Error (403): …\"``.\n53: \n54:     .. warning::\n55: \n56:        **Write paths MUST check ``not_found`` independently of\n57:        ``error_str``.** The soft-pass returns ``(DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n58:        True, None)`` for a missing agent when ``min_level <=\n59:        DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` — ``error_str`` is ``None`` so a caller\n60:        that only gates on ``terr`` will let an unregistered, fabricated\n61:        ``agent_id`` through. The soft-pass exists for read-only\n62:        ergonomics (``memclaw_list``, recall) where attribution is\n63:        cosmetic. On any path that persists records keyed to the caller-\n64:        supplied ``agent_id`` (memories, audit-log rows, evolve\n65:        outcomes, insights), an unregistered name corrupts the audit\n66:        trail because identity attribution becomes unverifiable.\n67: \n68:        Pattern to follow — see ``core_api/routes/evolve.py``::\n69: \n70:            _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(...)\n71:            if not_found:\n72:                raise HTTPException(\n73:                    status_code=403,\n74:                    detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered ...\",\n75:                )\n76:            if terr:\n77:                raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n78: \n79:        The same pattern is in ``routes/insights.py`` and the MCP\n80:        handlers ``memclaw_evolve`` / ``memclaw_insights`` in\n81:        ``mcp_server.py``. ``memclaw_list`` (read-only) intentionally\n82:        does NOT check ``not_found`` and is the canonical \"soft-pass\n83:        OK\" call site.\n84:     \"\"\"\n85:     from core_api.services.agent_service import lookup_agent\n86: \n87:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n88:     if agent is None:\n89:         # Soft-pass: a missing row is not a permission failure. Use the\n90:         # platform default trust so the gate matches what the agent would\n91:         # receive on its first write (when get_or_create_agent runs).\n92:         if min_level <= DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL:\n93:             return DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL, True, None\n94:         # Distinguish \"no row\" from a real ``trust_level`` denial so an\n95:         # operator debugging the 403 doesn't go looking for a row to\n96:         # upgrade that doesn't exist. The ``register the agent by\n97:         # writing one memory first`` hint matches the recovery path\n98:         # used elsewhere in the system (writes auto-create via\n99:         # ``get_or_create_agent``).\n100:         return (\n101:             DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n102:             True,\n103:             f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered \"\n104:             f\"(no row; effective trust {DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL} < required {min_level}). \"\n105:             f\"Register the agent by writing one memory first.\",\n106:         )\n107:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) if isinstance(agent, dict) else getattr(agent, \"trust_level\", 0)\n108:     if trust < min_level:\n109:         return (\n110:             trust,\n111:             False,\n112:             f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n113:         )\n114:     return trust, False, None\n115: \n116: \n117: def parse_trust_error(terr: str) -> str:\n118:     \"\"\"Strip the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` from an error produced by ``require_trust``.\n119: \n120:     REST routes use this to surface the underlying reason as the detail\n121:     of an ``HTTPException`` without leaking the MCP-style prefix. Uses\n122:     ``str.removeprefix`` which is a no-op when the prefix isn't present —\n123:     keeps the helper safe against future callers that feed in arbitrary\n124:     error strings.\n125:     \"\"\"\n126:     return terr.removeprefix(_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX)\n\n(End of file - total 126 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement.\n\nShared by the MCP handlers in ``core_api.mcp_server`` and the REST routes\nunder ``core_api.routes`` so both surfaces gate on the same rule without\nreaching into each other's private symbols.\n\n``require_trust`` returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass and\n``(trust, not_found, error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is a typed flag\nfor the \"agent row is missing\" case so callers can distinguish \"unknown\nid\" from \"known id with insufficient trust\" without parsing the error\nstring. The error string carries the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` constant so\nthe MCP handler convention stays in one place; ``parse_trust_error``\nstrips that prefix so REST routes can surface the bare detail through\nan ``HTTPException``.\n\nWhen the agent row is missing (``not_found=True``), the gate falls back\nto ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` rather than treating the row's absence as a\npermission failure: API-key admission already proved authorization, so\na fresh agent that hasn't yet been materialised by a write must still\nbe allowed to use any tool the tenant's default policy permits. Code","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement.\n\nShared by the MCP handlers in ``core_api.mcp_server`` and the REST routes\nunder ``core_api.routes`` so both surfaces gate on the same rule without\nreaching into each other's private symbols.\n\n``require_trust`` returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass and\n``(trust, not_found, error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is a typed flag\nfor the \"agent row is missing\" case so callers can distinguish \"unknown\nid\" from \"known id with insufficient trust\" without parsing the error\nstring. The error string carries the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` constant so\nthe MCP handler convention stays in one place; ``parse_trust_error``\nstrips that prefix so REST routes can surface the bare detail through\nan ``HTTPException``.\n\nWhen the agent row is missing (``not_found=True``), the gate falls back\nto ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` rather than treating the row's absence as a\npermission failure: API-key admission already proved authorization, so\na fresh agent that hasn't yet been materialised by a write must still\nbe allowed to use any tool the tenant's default policy permits. Code\npaths that need the row to exist (per-agent tuning, audit attribution)\nshould call ``get_or_create_agent`` explicitly — the soft-pass here\napplies only to the gate decision.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\n\n# Keep the prefix in one place so ``parse_trust_error`` and ``require_trust``\n# can't drift if someone edits one. ``str.removeprefix`` is a no-op when the\n# prefix isn't present, so parse_trust_error stays robust against future\n# error strings that happen not to start with it.\n_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX = \"Error (403): \"\n\n\nasync def require_trust(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    min_level: int,\n) -> tuple[int, bool, str | None]:\n    \"\"\"Look up the agent's trust level and gate on ``min_level``.\n\n    Returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass, ``(trust, not_found,\n    error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is ``True`` when no agent row\n    exists for ``(tenant_id, agent_id)``; in that case the effective\n    trust used for the gate decision is ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` (the\n    same level a freshly-registered agent receives). Error format\n    matches the wider MCP handler convention of ``\"Error (403): …\"``.\n\n    .. warning::\n\n       **Write paths MUST check ``not_found`` independently of\n       ``error_str``.** The soft-pass returns ``(DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n       True, None)`` for a missing agent when ``min_level <=\n       DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` — ``error_str`` is ``None`` so a caller\n       that only gates on ``terr`` will let an unregistered, fabricated\n       ``agent_id`` through. The soft-pass exists for read-only\n       ergonomics (``memclaw_list``, recall) where attribution is\n       cosmetic. On any path that persists records keyed to the caller-\n       supplied ``agent_id`` (memories, audit-log rows, evolve\n       outcomes, insights), an unregistered name corrupts the audit\n       trail because identity attribution becomes unverifiable.\n\n       Pattern to follow — see ``core_api/routes/evolve.py``::\n\n           _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(...)\n           if not_found:\n               raise HTTPException(\n                   status_code=403,\n                   detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered ...\",\n               )\n           if terr:\n               raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n\n       The same pattern is in ``routes/insights.py`` and the MCP\n       handlers ``memclaw_evolve`` / ``memclaw_insights`` in\n       ``mcp_server.py``. ``memclaw_list`` (read-only) intentionally\n       does NOT check ``not_found`` and is the canonical \"soft-pass\n       OK\" call site.\n    \"\"\"\n    from core_api.services.agent_service import lookup_agent\n\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n    if agent is None:\n        # Soft-pass: a missing row is not a permission failure. Use the\n        # platform default trust so the gate matches what the agent would\n        # receive on its first write (when get_or_create_agent runs).\n        if min_level <= DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL:\n            return DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL, True, None\n        # Distinguish \"no row\" from a real ``trust_level`` denial so an\n        # operator debugging the 403 doesn't go looking for a row to\n        # upgrade that doesn't exist. The ``register the agent by\n        # writing one memory first`` hint matches the recovery path\n        # used elsewhere in the system (writes auto-create via\n        # ``get_or_create_agent``).\n        return (\n            DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n            True,\n            f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered \"\n            f\"(no row; effective trust {DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL} < required {min_level}). \"\n            f\"Register the agent by writing one memory first.\",\n        )\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) if isinstance(agent, dict) else getattr(agent, \"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < min_level:\n        return (\n            trust,\n            False,\n            f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n        )\n    return trust, False, None\n\n\ndef parse_trust_error(terr: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Strip the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` from an error produced by ``require_trust``.\n\n    REST routes use this to surface the underlying reason as the detail\n    of an ``HTTPException`` without leaking the MCP-style prefix. Uses\n    ``str.removeprefix`` which is a no-op when the prefix isn't present —\n    keeps the helper safe against future callers that feed in arbitrary\n    error strings.\n    \"\"\"\n    return terr.removeprefix(_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":126,"totalLines":126,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py","time":{"start":1780727723692,"end":1780727723699}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9c9c8191b5f50ac8f07bcf67"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b691001cdZsVr0S2ftCir","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723704,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ossoLD6hO61kJv8QIdw3ySCZ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py","offset":1,"limit":320},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement for fleet-scoped access control.\"\"\"\n2: \n3: import logging\n4: from datetime import UTC, datetime\n5: from typing import Any\n6: \n7: from fastapi import HTTPException\n8: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n9: \n10: from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n11: from core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\n12: from core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n13: \n14: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n15: \n16: \n17: async def get_or_create_agent(\n18:     db: AsyncSession,\n19:     tenant_id: str,\n20:     agent_id: str,\n21:     fleet_id: str | None = None,\n22:     *,\n23:     require_approval: bool = False,\n24:     display_name: str | None = None,\n25:     install_id: str | None = None,\n26: ) -> dict:\n27:     \"\"\"Return the agent dict, creating it on first encounter.\n28: \n29:     The storage API handles upsert semantics and race-condition safety.\n30: \n31:     ``display_name`` and ``install_id`` (Task 6) are accepted optionally\n32:     on every call. On creation they're persisted; on lookup of an\n33:     existing row, ``display_name`` is refreshed if the new value\n34:     differs (so a renamed machine propagates) and ``install_id`` is\n35:     backfilled when previously NULL but never overwritten — the\n36:     install identity is stable for the row's lifetime.\n37:     \"\"\"\n38:     sc = get_storage_client()\n39:     agent = await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n40:     if agent:\n41:         # Backfill fleet_id if the agent was registered without one,\n42:         # refresh display_name when it differs (hostname change), and\n43:         # stamp install_id on first contact post-plugin-upgrade.\n44:         backfill: dict = {}\n45:         if agent.get(\"fleet_id\") is None and fleet_id is not None:\n46:             backfill[\"fleet_id\"] = fleet_id\n47:         if display_name is not None and agent.get(\"display_name\") != display_name:\n48:             backfill[\"display_name\"] = display_name\n49:         if install_id is not None and agent.get(\"install_id\") is None:\n50:             backfill[\"install_id\"] = install_id\n51:         if backfill:\n52:             agent.update(backfill)\n53:             agent[\"updated_at\"] = datetime.now(UTC)\n54:             await sc.create_or_update_agent({\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"agent_id\": agent_id, **backfill})\n55:         return agent\n56: \n57:     # Legacy-main carryover: pre-Task6 plugins all defaulted to\n58:     # ``agent_id=\"main\"``, so an upgrade from those creates a brand-new\n59:     # ``main-{install_id}`` row and orphans the old \"main\" row's\n60:     # tuning state. When this is a fresh ``main-{install_id}`` create\n61:     # for a tenant/fleet that has a legacy \"main\" row, copy\n62:     # ``trust_level`` and ``search_profile`` forward so the upgraded\n63:     # plugin keeps the operator's prior calibration. Bounded scope:\n64:     #   - only triggers for ``main-{install_id}`` ids (not arbitrary\n65:     #     custom agents) so a deliberate new agent doesn't accidentally\n66:     #     inherit\n67:     #   - skipped when ``require_approval=True`` (the explicit\n68:     #     \"start at 0\" path)\n69:     #   - leaves the legacy row intact so its memories stay queryable\n70:     #     under ``agent_id=\"main\"`` for admin recovery; operators\n71:     #     decide later whether to delete or keep as archive\n72:     inherited_trust: int | None = None\n73:     inherited_search_profile: dict[str, Any] | None = None\n74:     if not require_approval and install_id is not None and agent_id == f\"main-{install_id}\":\n75:         legacy = await sc.get_agent(\"main\", tenant_id)\n76:         if legacy and (fleet_id is None or legacy.get(\"fleet_id\") == fleet_id):\n77:             inherited_trust = legacy.get(\"trust_level\")\n78:             inherited_search_profile = legacy.get(\"search_profile\")\n79:             logger.info(\n80:                 \"carrying forward legacy 'main' agent state to install-scoped id\",\n81:                 extra={\n82:                     \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n83:                     \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n84:                     \"new_agent_id\": agent_id,\n85:                     \"inherited_trust\": inherited_trust,\n86:                 },\n87:             )\n88: \n89:     initial_trust = (\n90:         inherited_trust if inherited_trust is not None else (0 if require_approval else DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL)\n91:     )\n92:     create_payload: dict[str, Any] = {\n93:         \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n94:         \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n95:         \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n96:         \"display_name\": display_name,\n97:         \"install_id\": install_id,\n98:         \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n99:     }\n100:     if inherited_search_profile is not None:\n101:         create_payload[\"search_profile\"] = inherited_search_profile\n102:     agent = await sc.create_or_update_agent(create_payload)\n103:     await log_action(\n104:         db,\n105:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n106:         agent_id=agent_id,\n107:         action=\"agent_registered\",\n108:         resource_type=\"agent\",\n109:         resource_id=agent.get(\"id\"),\n110:         detail={\n111:             \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n112:             \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n113:             \"display_name\": display_name,\n114:             \"install_id\": install_id,\n115:             \"carried_from_legacy_main\": inherited_trust is not None,\n116:         },\n117:     )\n118:     return agent\n119: \n120: \n121: async def lookup_agent(db: AsyncSession, tenant_id: str, agent_id: str) -> dict | None:\n122:     sc = get_storage_client()\n123:     return await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n124: \n125: \n126: async def enforce_fleet_write(\n127:     db: AsyncSession,\n128:     tenant_id: str,\n129:     agent_id: str,\n130:     fleet_id: str | None,\n131: ) -> dict:\n132:     \"\"\"Enforce write permissions. Returns the agent (auto-created if new).\"\"\"\n133:     agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id)\n134: \n135:     # Agents can always write to their home fleet (or tenant-wide if no fleet specified)\n136:     if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n137:         return agent\n138: \n139:     # Cross-fleet write requires admin (level >= 3)\n140:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n141:     if trust < 3:\n142:         raise HTTPException(\n143:             status_code=403,\n144:             detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not writable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n145:         )\n146:     return agent\n147: \n148: \n149: async def enforce_fleet_read(\n150:     db: AsyncSession,\n151:     tenant_id: str,\n152:     agent_id: str,\n153:     fleet_id: str | None,\n154: ) -> None:\n155:     \"\"\"Enforce read permissions for search/list (read-only — never creates agents).\"\"\"\n156:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n157: \n158:     # Unknown agent — allow the read (agent registration happens on writes)\n159:     if not agent:\n160:         return\n161: \n162:     # Reading own fleet or tenant-wide is always allowed\n163:     if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n164:         return\n165: \n166:     # Cross-fleet read requires level >= 2\n167:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n168:     if trust < 2:\n169:         raise HTTPException(\n170:             status_code=403,\n171:             detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not readable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n172:         )\n173: \n174: \n175: async def authorize_memory_access(\n176:     db: AsyncSession,\n177:     tenant_id: str,\n178:     caller_agent_id: str | None,\n179:     *,\n180:     visibility: str | None,\n181:     owner_agent_id: str | None,\n182:     fleet_id: str | None,\n183:     write: bool = False,\n184: ) -> bool:\n185:     \"\"\"Authorize a *by-id* memory access against the fleet/scope contract.\n186: \n187:     By-id handlers (``GET/PATCH/DELETE /memories/{id}`` and the MCP\n188:     ``read``/``lineage``/``transition``/``update``/``delete`` ops) historically\n189:     authorized on ``tenant_id`` alone, while the list/search paths additionally\n190:     enforce ``scope_agent`` ownership (``memory_repository`` visibility\n191:     predicate) and the cross-fleet trust ladder (``enforce_fleet_read``). That\n192:     asymmetry let any same-tenant agent credential read or mutate a peer's\n193:     fleet/agent-scoped row by id (BOLA/IDOR). This helper restores parity so\n194:     every surface enforces the same contract.\n195: \n196:     Returns ``True`` if ``caller_agent_id`` may access the row.\n197: \n198:     - ``caller_agent_id is None`` → a tenant-scoped user/dashboard credential\n199:       (no gateway ``X-Agent-ID``) → full tenant access, unchanged. The agent\n200:       isolation boundary only applies to agent-scoped credentials.\n201:     - ``scope_agent`` → author-only.\n202:     - ``scope_org`` → tenant-global (mirrors ``scored_search``'s rule that\n203:       org-scoped rows escape fleet scoping).\n204:     - ``scope_team`` / default → fleet-gated: own fleet (or fleet-less rows)\n205:       always; cross-fleet requires ``trust_level >= 2`` for reads, ``>= 3`` for\n206:       writes (mirrors ``enforce_fleet_read`` / ``enforce_fleet_write``).\n207:     \"\"\"\n208:     if not caller_agent_id:\n209:         return True\n210:     if visibility == \"scope_agent\":\n211:         return owner_agent_id == caller_agent_id\n212:     if visibility == \"scope_org\":\n213:         return True\n214:     # scope_team / unknown visibility: fleet-gated by the trust ladder.\n215:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id)\n216:     if not agent:\n217:         # Unknown agent — mirror enforce_fleet_read's allow-on-unknown\n218:         # (registration happens on writes; reads of an unregistered identity\n219:         # are not the isolation boundary this helper guards).\n220:         return True\n221:     if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n222:         return True\n223:     return agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) >= (3 if write else 2)\n224: \n225: \n226: async def enforce_memory_read(\n227:     db: AsyncSession,\n228:     tenant_id: str,\n229:     caller_agent_id: str | None,\n230:     memory: Any,\n231: ) -> None:\n232:     \"\"\"Raise 404 if ``caller_agent_id`` may not read ``memory`` (an ORM row).\n233: \n234:     404 (not 403) is deliberate: it mirrors the list/search contract where an\n235:     out-of-scope row simply does not appear, and avoids confirming the\n236:     existence of another fleet's/agent's memory_id to an unauthorized caller.\n237:     \"\"\"\n238:     allowed = await authorize_memory_access(\n239:         db,\n240:         tenant_id,\n241:         caller_agent_id,\n242:         visibility=getattr(memory, \"visibility\", None),\n243:         owner_agent_id=getattr(memory, \"agent_id\", None),\n244:         fleet_id=getattr(memory, \"fleet_id\", None),\n245:     )\n246:     if not allowed:\n247:         raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail=\"Memory not found\")\n248: \n249: \n250: async def enforce_delete(\n251:     db: AsyncSession,\n252:     tenant_id: str,\n253:     agent_id: str,\n254: ) -> None:\n255:     \"\"\"Enforce delete permissions.\"\"\"\n256:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n257:     if not agent:\n258:         raise HTTPException(\n259:             status_code=403,\n260:             detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered and cannot delete memories.\",\n261:         )\n262: \n263:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n264:     if trust < 3:\n265:         raise HTTPException(\n266:             status_code=403,\n267:             detail=f\"access policy: principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}' are not permitted to delete memories.\",\n268:         )\n269: \n270: \n271: async def enforce_update(\n272:     db: AsyncSession,\n273:     tenant_id: str,\n274:     agent_id: str,\n275:     memory_owner_agent_id: str,\n276: ) -> None:\n277:     \"\"\"Enforce update permissions. Level 0-2 can only update own memories; level 3 can update any.\"\"\"\n278:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n279:     if not agent:\n280:         raise HTTPException(\n281:             status_code=403,\n282:             detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered and cannot update memories.\",\n283:         )\n284:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n285:     if trust == 0:\n286:         raise HTTPException(\n287:             status_code=403,\n288:             detail=f\"access policy: agent '{agent_id}' is restricted from updates.\",\n289:         )\n290:     if trust < 3 and agent_id != memory_owner_agent_id:\n291:         raise HTTPException(\n292:             status_code=403,\n293:             detail=f\"access policy: agent '{agent_id}' may only update its own memories.\",\n294:         )\n295: \n296: \n297: async def backfill_agents(db: AsyncSession) -> int:\n298:     \"\"\"Create agent rows for any (tenant_id, agent_id) pairs in memories that don't have one yet.\"\"\"\n299:     sc = get_storage_client()\n300:     # Use the first available tenant_id — in standalone mode there's only one\n301:     from core_api.standalone import get_standalone_tenant_id\n302: \n303:     tenant_id = get_standalone_tenant_id()\n304:     result = await sc.backfill_from_memories(tenant_id)\n305:     return result.get(\"count\", 0)\n306: \n307: \n308: async def update_trust_level(\n309:     db: AsyncSession,\n310:     tenant_id: str,\n311:     agent_id: str,\n312:     trust_level: int,\n313:     fleet_id: str | None = None,\n314: ) -> dict:\n315:     \"\"\"Update an agent's trust level (and optionally fleet). Returns the updated agent.\"\"\"\n316:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n317:     if not agent:\n318:         raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' not found\")\n319: \n320:     sc = get_storage_client()\n\n(Showing lines 1-320 of 327. Use offset=321 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement for fleet-scoped access control.\"\"\"\n\nimport logging\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nasync def get_or_create_agent(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement for fleet-scoped access control.\"\"\"\n\nimport logging\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nasync def get_or_create_agent(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None = None,\n    *,\n    require_approval: bool = False,\n    display_name: str | None = None,\n    install_id: str | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Return the agent dict, creating it on first encounter.\n\n    The storage API handles upsert semantics and race-condition safety.\n\n    ``display_name`` and ``install_id`` (Task 6) are accepted optionally\n    on every call. On creation they're persisted; on lookup of an\n    existing row, ``display_name`` is refreshed if the new value\n    differs (so a renamed machine propagates) and ``install_id`` is\n    backfilled when previously NULL but never overwritten — the\n    install identity is stable for the row's lifetime.\n    \"\"\"\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    agent = await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n    if agent:\n        # Backfill fleet_id if the agent was registered without one,\n        # refresh display_name when it differs (hostname change), and\n        # stamp install_id on first contact post-plugin-upgrade.\n        backfill: dict = {}\n        if agent.get(\"fleet_id\") is None and fleet_id is not None:\n            backfill[\"fleet_id\"] = fleet_id\n        if display_name is not None and agent.get(\"display_name\") != display_name:\n            backfill[\"display_name\"] = display_name\n        if install_id is not None and agent.get(\"install_id\") is None:\n            backfill[\"install_id\"] = install_id\n        if backfill:\n            agent.update(backfill)\n            agent[\"updated_at\"] = datetime.now(UTC)\n            await sc.create_or_update_agent({\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"agent_id\": agent_id, **backfill})\n        return agent\n\n    # Legacy-main carryover: pre-Task6 plugins all defaulted to\n    # ``agent_id=\"main\"``, so an upgrade from those creates a brand-new\n    # ``main-{install_id}`` row and orphans the old \"main\" row's\n    # tuning state. When this is a fresh ``main-{install_id}`` create\n    # for a tenant/fleet that has a legacy \"main\" row, copy\n    # ``trust_level`` and ``search_profile`` forward so the upgraded\n    # plugin keeps the operator's prior calibration. Bounded scope:\n    #   - only triggers for ``main-{install_id}`` ids (not arbitrary\n    #     custom agents) so a deliberate new agent doesn't accidentally\n    #     inherit\n    #   - skipped when ``require_approval=True`` (the explicit\n    #     \"start at 0\" path)\n    #   - leaves the legacy row intact so its memories stay queryable\n    #     under ``agent_id=\"main\"`` for admin recovery; operators\n    #     decide later whether to delete or keep as archive\n    inherited_trust: int | None = None\n    inherited_search_profile: dict[str, Any] | None = None\n    if not require_approval and install_id is not None and agent_id == f\"main-{install_id}\":\n        legacy = await sc.get_agent(\"main\", tenant_id)\n        if legacy and (fleet_id is None or legacy.get(\"fleet_id\") == fleet_id):\n            inherited_trust = legacy.get(\"trust_level\")\n            inherited_search_profile = legacy.get(\"search_profile\")\n            logger.info(\n                \"carrying forward legacy 'main' agent state to install-scoped id\",\n                extra={\n                    \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n                    \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n                    \"new_agent_id\": agent_id,\n                    \"inherited_trust\": inherited_trust,\n                },\n            )\n\n    initial_trust = (\n        inherited_trust if inherited_trust is not None else (0 if require_approval else DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL)\n    )\n    create_payload: dict[str, Any] = {\n        \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n        \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n        \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n        \"display_name\": display_name,\n        \"install_id\": install_id,\n        \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n    }\n    if inherited_search_profile is not None:\n        create_payload[\"search_profile\"] = inherited_search_profile\n    agent = await sc.create_or_update_agent(create_payload)\n    await log_action(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        agent_id=agent_id,\n        action=\"agent_registered\",\n        resource_type=\"agent\",\n        resource_id=agent.get(\"id\"),\n        detail={\n            \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n            \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n            \"display_name\": display_name,\n            \"install_id\": install_id,\n            \"carried_from_legacy_main\": inherited_trust is not None,\n        },\n    )\n    return agent\n\n\nasync def lookup_agent(db: AsyncSession, tenant_id: str, agent_id: str) -> dict | None:\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    return await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n\n\nasync def enforce_fleet_write(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Enforce write permissions. Returns the agent (auto-created if new).\"\"\"\n    agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id)\n\n    # Agents can always write to their home fleet (or tenant-wide if no fleet specified)\n    if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n        return agent\n\n    # Cross-fleet write requires admin (level >= 3)\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < 3:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not writable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n        )\n    return agent\n\n\nasync def enforce_fleet_read(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Enforce read permissions for search/list (read-only — never creates agents).\"\"\"\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n\n    # Unknown agent — allow the read (agent registration happens on writes)\n    if not agent:\n        return\n\n    # Reading own fleet or tenant-wide is always allowed\n    if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n        return\n\n    # Cross-fleet read requires level >= 2\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < 2:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not readable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n        )\n\n\nasync def authorize_memory_access(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    caller_agent_id: str | None,\n    *,\n    visibility: str | None,\n    owner_agent_id: str | None,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n    write: bool = False,\n) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Authorize a *by-id* memory access against the fleet/scope contract.\n\n    By-id handlers (``GET/PATCH/DELETE /memories/{id}`` and the MCP\n    ``read``/``lineage``/``transition``/``update``/``delete`` ops) historically\n    authorized on ``tenant_id`` alone, while the list/search paths additionally\n    enforce ``scope_agent`` ownership (``memory_repository`` visibility\n    predicate) and the cross-fleet trust ladder (``enforce_fleet_read``). That\n    asymmetry let any same-tenant agent credential read or mutate a peer's\n    fleet/agent-scoped row by id (BOLA/IDOR). This helper restores parity so\n    every surface enforces the same contract.\n\n    Returns ``True`` if ``caller_agent_id`` may access the row.\n\n    - ``caller_agent_id is None`` → a tenant-scoped user/dashboard credential\n      (no gateway ``X-Agent-ID``) → full tenant access, unchanged. The agent\n      isolation boundary only applies to agent-scoped credentials.\n    - ``scope_agent`` → author-only.\n    - ``scope_org`` → tenant-global (mirrors ``scored_search``'s rule that\n      org-scoped rows escape fleet scoping).\n    - ``scope_team`` / default → fleet-gated: own fleet (or fleet-less rows)\n      always; cross-fleet requires ``trust_level >= 2`` for reads, ``>= 3`` for\n      writes (mirrors ``enforce_fleet_read`` / ``enforce_fleet_write``).\n    \"\"\"\n    if not caller_agent_id:\n        return True\n    if visibility == \"scope_agent\":\n        return owner_agent_id == caller_agent_id\n    if visibility == \"scope_org\":\n        return True\n    # scope_team / unknown visibility: fleet-gated by the trust ladder.\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, caller_agent_id)\n    if not agent:\n        # Unknown agent — mirror enforce_fleet_read's allow-on-unknown\n        # (registration happens on writes; reads of an unregistered identity\n        # are not the isolation boundary this helper guards).\n        return True\n    if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n        return True\n    return agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) >= (3 if write else 2)\n\n\nasync def enforce_memory_read(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    caller_agent_id: str | None,\n    memory: Any,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Raise 404 if ``caller_agent_id`` may not read ``memory`` (an ORM row).\n\n    404 (not 403) is deliberate: it mirrors the list/search contract where an\n    out-of-scope row simply does not appear, and avoids confirming the\n    existence of another fleet's/agent's memory_id to an unauthorized caller.\n    \"\"\"\n    allowed = await authorize_memory_access(\n        db,\n        tenant_id,\n        caller_agent_id,\n        visibility=getattr(memory, \"visibility\", None),\n        owner_agent_id=getattr(memory, \"agent_id\", None),\n        fleet_id=getattr(memory, \"fleet_id\", None),\n    )\n    if not allowed:\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail=\"Memory not found\")\n\n\nasync def enforce_delete(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Enforce delete permissions.\"\"\"\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n    if not agent:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered and cannot delete memories.\",\n        )\n\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < 3:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"access policy: principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}' are not permitted to delete memories.\",\n        )\n\n\nasync def enforce_update(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    memory_owner_agent_id: str,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Enforce update permissions. Level 0-2 can only update own memories; level 3 can update any.\"\"\"\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n    if not agent:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered and cannot update memories.\",\n        )\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust == 0:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"access policy: agent '{agent_id}' is restricted from updates.\",\n        )\n    if trust < 3 and agent_id != memory_owner_agent_id:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"access policy: agent '{agent_id}' may only update its own memories.\",\n        )\n\n\nasync def backfill_agents(db: AsyncSession) -> int:\n    \"\"\"Create agent rows for any (tenant_id, agent_id) pairs in memories that don't have one yet.\"\"\"\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    # Use the first available tenant_id — in standalone mode there's only one\n    from core_api.standalone import get_standalone_tenant_id\n\n    tenant_id = get_standalone_tenant_id()\n    result = await sc.backfill_from_memories(tenant_id)\n    return result.get(\"count\", 0)\n\n\nasync def update_trust_level(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    trust_level: int,\n    fleet_id: str | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Update an agent's trust level (and optionally fleet). Returns the updated agent.\"\"\"\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n    if not agent:\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=404, detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' not found\")\n\n    sc = get_storage_client()","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":320,"totalLines":327,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py","time":{"start":1780727723695,"end":1780727723703}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cb0819196638f50b7b6e7f4"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6ad001CzA2DCjFgr2wtE","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723710,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_JEXSHtORSW7uODoB4guqNyHM","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Audit-event ingestion entrypoint.\n2: \n3: ``log_action`` is the only public surface — every memory mutation calls\n4: it via the configured ``ServiceHooks`` (see ``core_api.app.lifespan``).\n5: \n6: CAURA-628 (2026-04-29): the legacy shape POSTed one audit event per\n7: mutation directly to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk storms that\n8: created up to N HTTP-POSTs-per-bulk-create on the storage-api connection\n9: pool + serialised tenant B's audit traffic behind tenant A's storm at\n10: the AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock. ``log_action`` now\n11: enqueues into a process-local ``AuditEventQueue``; a background flusher\n12: batches events and writes them via ``POST /audit-logs/bulk``.\n13: \n14: The synchronous-POST fallback path runs when the queue is not active\n15: (early startup, tests that didn't wire it, intentional kill-switch via\n16: ``set_audit_queue(None)``). That fallback preserves the legacy\n17: behaviour byte-for-byte so a queue-side bug can't silently drop audit\n18: events; an operator can fall back to the legacy path during an incident\n19: without a redeploy.\n20: \"\"\"\n21: \n22: from __future__ import annotations\n23: \n24: from uuid import UUID\n25: \n26: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n27: \n28: from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n29: from core_api.services.audit_queue import get_audit_queue\n30: \n31: \n32: async def log_action(\n33:     db: AsyncSession,\n34:     *,\n35:     tenant_id: str,\n36:     agent_id: str | None = None,\n37:     action: str,\n38:     resource_type: str,\n39:     resource_id: UUID | None = None,\n40:     detail: dict | None = None,\n41: ) -> None:\n42:     \"\"\"Record an audit event. Async-batched via queue when available;\n43:     falls through to a synchronous POST otherwise.\n44: \n45:     ``db`` is unused (audit persistence is owned by the storage layer)\n46:     but kept in the signature for back-compat with the ``ServiceHooks``\n47:     contract — callers pass it through; switching them all to drop the\n48:     arg is a separate, scoped change.\n49:     \"\"\"\n50:     payload = {\n51:         \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n52:         \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n53:         \"action\": action,\n54:         \"resource_type\": resource_type,\n55:         \"resource_id\": str(resource_id) if resource_id else None,\n56:         \"detail\": detail,\n57:     }\n58:     queue = get_audit_queue()\n59:     if queue is not None:\n60:         # Non-blocking enqueue. Overflow is mapped to a structured\n61:         # warning + drop counter inside the queue — the request hot\n62:         # path stays fast even when storage-api is degraded.\n63:         queue.enqueue(payload)\n64:         return\n65: \n66:     # Fallback: synchronous POST. Same shape as pre-CAURA-628.\n67:     sc = get_storage_client()\n68:     await sc.create_audit_log(payload)\n69: \n70: \n71: async def log_cross_tenant_read(\n72:     db: AsyncSession,\n73:     *,\n74:     home_tenant_id: str | None,\n75:     home_agent_id: str | None,\n76:     source_tenants: list[str],\n77:     surface: str,\n78:     result_count_by_tenant: dict[str, int] | None = None,\n79:     query_summary: str | None = None,\n80: ) -> None:\n81:     \"\"\"Emit a ``cross_tenant_read`` audit event per source tenant touched.\n82: \n83:     Called from read handlers after they widen their query via\n84:     ``readable_tenant_ids``. The event is logged TO each source tenant\n85:     (``tenant_id=src``) so per-tenant audit-log queries surface \"who\n86:     read FROM my tenant\" — including the home tenant_id and agent_id\n87:     of the caller in ``detail`` for forensic traceability.\n88: \n89:     No-op when ``source_tenants`` is empty (single-tenant reads).\n90:     Emission is via the same async queue ``log_action`` uses — overflow\n91:     handling and back-pressure are identical.\n92: \n93:     Hook for ``AuthContext.source_tenants_for_audit()`` — callers pass\n94:     that method's return value as ``source_tenants``.\n95:     \"\"\"\n96:     if not source_tenants:\n97:         return\n98:     for src in source_tenants:\n99:         await log_action(\n100:             db,\n101:             tenant_id=src,\n102:             agent_id=home_agent_id,\n103:             action=\"cross_tenant_read\",\n104:             resource_type=surface,\n105:             detail={\n106:                 \"home_tenant_id\": home_tenant_id,\n107:                 \"home_agent_id\": home_agent_id,\n108:                 \"result_count_from_this_tenant\": ((result_count_by_tenant or {}).get(src)),\n109:                 \"query_summary\": query_summary,\n110:             },\n111:         )\n\n(End of file - total 111 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Audit-event ingestion entrypoint.\n\n``log_action`` is the only public surface — every memory mutation calls\nit via the configured ``ServiceHooks`` (see ``core_api.app.lifespan``).\n\nCAURA-628 (2026-04-29): the legacy shape POSTed one audit event per\nmutation directly to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk storms that\ncreated up to N HTTP-POSTs-per-bulk-create on the storage-api connection\npool + serialised tenant B's audit traffic behind tenant A's storm at\nthe AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock. ``log_action`` now\nenqueues into a process-local ``AuditEventQueue``; a background flusher\nbatches events and writes them via ``POST /audit-logs/bulk``.\n\nThe synchronous-POST fallback path runs when the queue is not active\n(early startup, tests that didn't wire it, intentional kill-switch via\n``set_audit_queue(None)``). That fallback preserves the legacy\nbehaviour byte-for-byte so a queue-side bug can't silently drop audit\nevents; an operator can fall back to the legacy path during an incident\nwithout a redeploy.\n\"\"\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Audit-event ingestion entrypoint.\n\n``log_action`` is the only public surface — every memory mutation calls\nit via the configured ``ServiceHooks`` (see ``core_api.app.lifespan``).\n\nCAURA-628 (2026-04-29): the legacy shape POSTed one audit event per\nmutation directly to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk storms that\ncreated up to N HTTP-POSTs-per-bulk-create on the storage-api connection\npool + serialised tenant B's audit traffic behind tenant A's storm at\nthe AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock. ``log_action`` now\nenqueues into a process-local ``AuditEventQueue``; a background flusher\nbatches events and writes them via ``POST /audit-logs/bulk``.\n\nThe synchronous-POST fallback path runs when the queue is not active\n(early startup, tests that didn't wire it, intentional kill-switch via\n``set_audit_queue(None)``). That fallback preserves the legacy\nbehaviour byte-for-byte so a queue-side bug can't silently drop audit\nevents; an operator can fall back to the legacy path during an incident\nwithout a redeploy.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom uuid import UUID\n\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.services.audit_queue import get_audit_queue\n\n\nasync def log_action(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    *,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str | None = None,\n    action: str,\n    resource_type: str,\n    resource_id: UUID | None = None,\n    detail: dict | None = None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Record an audit event. Async-batched via queue when available;\n    falls through to a synchronous POST otherwise.\n\n    ``db`` is unused (audit persistence is owned by the storage layer)\n    but kept in the signature for back-compat with the ``ServiceHooks``\n    contract — callers pass it through; switching them all to drop the\n    arg is a separate, scoped change.\n    \"\"\"\n    payload = {\n        \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n        \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n        \"action\": action,\n        \"resource_type\": resource_type,\n        \"resource_id\": str(resource_id) if resource_id else None,\n        \"detail\": detail,\n    }\n    queue = get_audit_queue()\n    if queue is not None:\n        # Non-blocking enqueue. Overflow is mapped to a structured\n        # warning + drop counter inside the queue — the request hot\n        # path stays fast even when storage-api is degraded.\n        queue.enqueue(payload)\n        return\n\n    # Fallback: synchronous POST. Same shape as pre-CAURA-628.\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    await sc.create_audit_log(payload)\n\n\nasync def log_cross_tenant_read(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    *,\n    home_tenant_id: str | None,\n    home_agent_id: str | None,\n    source_tenants: list[str],\n    surface: str,\n    result_count_by_tenant: dict[str, int] | None = None,\n    query_summary: str | None = None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Emit a ``cross_tenant_read`` audit event per source tenant touched.\n\n    Called from read handlers after they widen their query via\n    ``readable_tenant_ids``. The event is logged TO each source tenant\n    (``tenant_id=src``) so per-tenant audit-log queries surface \"who\n    read FROM my tenant\" — including the home tenant_id and agent_id\n    of the caller in ``detail`` for forensic traceability.\n\n    No-op when ``source_tenants`` is empty (single-tenant reads).\n    Emission is via the same async queue ``log_action`` uses — overflow\n    handling and back-pressure are identical.\n\n    Hook for ``AuthContext.source_tenants_for_audit()`` — callers pass\n    that method's return value as ``source_tenants``.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not source_tenants:\n        return\n    for src in source_tenants:\n        await log_action(\n            db,\n            tenant_id=src,\n            agent_id=home_agent_id,\n            action=\"cross_tenant_read\",\n            resource_type=surface,\n            detail={\n                \"home_tenant_id\": home_tenant_id,\n                \"home_agent_id\": home_agent_id,\n                \"result_count_from_this_tenant\": ((result_count_by_tenant or {}).get(src)),\n                \"query_summary\": query_summary,\n            },\n        )","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":111,"totalLines":111,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py","time":{"start":1780727723701,"end":1780727723709}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cb88191ac2e1672e01b14d4"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6b0001D8nPXEAMPkF9rn","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723718,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_62NZuHCJmkGcSdKD0r8GjgAY","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_queue.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_queue.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"In-memory audit-event queue + background batched flusher (CAURA-628).\n2: \n3: Pre-CAURA-628 every memory write triggered a fire-and-forget background\n4: task that POSTed one audit event to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk\n5: storms (100-item batches x tenant A's 20-concurrent storm = up to 2000\n6: audit POSTs in flight) those calls saturated the storage-api per-tenant\n7: slot AND piled up on the AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock,\n8: queueing tenant B's gentle audit traffic behind tenant A's fan-out.\n9: That cross-tenant queueing is the residual contention the CAURA-627\n10: deep-dive identified as the dominant remaining ``noisy-neighbor-write``\n11: cause, after the LLM-pool fix in #34 and the dead-index drop in #35.\n12: \n13: This module replaces the per-event POST with an in-memory ``asyncio``\n14: queue + a background flusher that batches events and writes them to a\n15: new ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` endpoint. Flush triggers are first-of:\n16: \n17:   - ``audit_queue_flush_threshold`` events accumulated (50 by default)\n18:   - ``audit_queue_flush_interval_seconds`` elapsed since last flush (1s)\n19: \n20: Per-event memory overhead is small (~200 bytes for an audit dict at the\n21: default sizes), so a 10000-event cap fits in ~2 MiB per worker process —\n22: plenty of headroom over the realistic worst-case storm rate.\n23: \n24: Backpressure: the queue is bounded. If writers fill the queue faster\n25: than the flusher drains it (storage-api degraded, or a sustained burst\n26: larger than the cap), new events are dropped with a structured warning\n27: counter rather than blocking the request hot path. Audit is not on the\n28: critical correctness path; loss of a few events under sustained\n29: overload is preferable to defeating the whole point of async ingestion\n30: by blocking writers.\n31: \"\"\"\n32: \n33: from __future__ import annotations\n34: \n35: import asyncio\n36: import logging\n37: \n38: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n39: \n40: \n41: class AuditEventQueue:\n42:     \"\"\"Bounded in-memory queue for audit events with a background flusher.\n43: \n44:     Lifecycle: ``start()`` from FastAPI lifespan startup,\n45:     ``stop(timeout=...)`` from shutdown. Both are idempotent so a\n46:     re-import in tests doesn't double-start the task.\n47:     \"\"\"\n48: \n49:     def __init__(\n50:         self,\n51:         *,\n52:         max_queue_size: int,\n53:         flush_threshold: int,\n54:         flush_interval_seconds: float,\n55:         flush_callable,  # async (events: list[dict]) -> None\n56:         chunk_size: int = 500,\n57:     ) -> None:\n58:         self._max_queue_size = max_queue_size\n59:         self._flush_threshold = flush_threshold\n60:         self._flush_interval = flush_interval_seconds\n61:         self._flush_callable = flush_callable\n62:         # ``chunk_size`` caps the per-call batch given to ``flush_callable``.\n63:         # The storage-side ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` endpoint enforces\n64:         # ``_MAX_BATCH_SIZE = 500``; if the queue ever holds more than\n65:         # that (e.g. storage-api was degraded and the queue built up),\n66:         # a single uncapped flush would 422 and lose every drained\n67:         # event. Slicing the drained list into chunks keeps each flush\n68:         # call within the storage cap, and per-chunk failure isolation\n69:         # means a bad chunk doesn't take down the rest of the drain.\n70:         # Default matches the storage-side cap exactly; tests pass\n71:         # ``chunk_size=1`` to exercise the slicing path without\n72:         # depending on the storage-side constant.\n73:         self._chunk_size = chunk_size\n74:         self._queue: asyncio.Queue[dict] = asyncio.Queue(maxsize=max_queue_size)\n75:         self._flusher_task: asyncio.Task[None] | None = None\n76:         self._stopping = asyncio.Event()\n77:         self._dropped_count = 0\n78:         self._flushed_count = 0\n79:         self._failed_count = 0\n80:         self._wake_event = asyncio.Event()  # set when threshold reached\n81: \n82:     @property\n83:     def dropped_count(self) -> int:\n84:         \"\"\"Events rejected at enqueue time because the queue was full.\"\"\"\n85:         return self._dropped_count\n86: \n87:     @property\n88:     def flushed_count(self) -> int:\n89:         \"\"\"Events successfully written via the flush callable.\"\"\"\n90:         return self._flushed_count\n91: \n92:     @property\n93:     def failed_count(self) -> int:\n94:         \"\"\"Events drained from the queue but lost when the flush callable\n95:         raised. Distinct from ``dropped_count`` (full-queue rejection)\n96:         so an operator can distinguish \"writers outpacing the flusher\"\n97:         from \"storage-api failing the write\" in dashboards.\"\"\"\n98:         return self._failed_count\n99: \n100:     @property\n101:     def queue_size(self) -> int:\n102:         return self._queue.qsize()\n103: \n104:     def enqueue(self, event: dict) -> None:\n105:         \"\"\"Non-blocking enqueue. Drops + warns when the queue is full.\n106: \n107:         Synchronous (no ``await``) so callers in fire-and-forget paths\n108:         don't pay an extra event-loop hop. ``Queue.put_nowait`` returns\n109:         immediately when there's room; raises ``QueueFull`` otherwise,\n110:         which we map to a counter + structured warning rather than\n111:         propagating to the caller (audit isn't on the correctness\n112:         path; dropping is preferable to blocking the request).\n113:         \"\"\"\n114:         try:\n115:             self._queue.put_nowait(event)\n116:         except asyncio.QueueFull:\n117:             self._dropped_count += 1\n118:             # Log every 100th drop so a sustained overload produces a\n119:             # finite, informative log volume rather than one line per\n120:             # dropped event. A single first-drop line still surfaces\n121:             # immediately so the issue is visible.\n122:             if self._dropped_count == 1 or self._dropped_count % 100 == 0:\n123:                 logger.warning(\n124:                     \"audit queue full; dropped %d events so far \"\n125:                     \"(max_queue_size=%d, flush behind storage-api?)\",\n126:                     self._dropped_count,\n127:                     self._max_queue_size,\n128:                 )\n129:             return\n130:         # Wake the flusher early when we reach the batch threshold so a\n131:         # storm doesn't have to wait for the interval timer.\n132:         if self._queue.qsize() >= self._flush_threshold:\n133:             self._wake_event.set()\n134: \n135:     async def start(self) -> None:\n136:         \"\"\"Idempotent: a second call is a no-op.\"\"\"\n137:         if self._flusher_task is not None and not self._flusher_task.done():\n138:             return\n139:         self._stopping.clear()\n140:         self._flusher_task = asyncio.create_task(self._flusher_loop(), name=\"audit-queue-flusher\")\n141: \n142:     async def stop(self, *, timeout: float = 5.0) -> None:\n143:         \"\"\"Signal the flusher to drain pending events and exit.\n144: \n145:         Waits up to ``timeout`` seconds for the final flush. If the\n146:         deadline expires (storage-api hung), the flusher task is\n147:         cancelled and any still-in-queue events are lost — the\n148:         alternative is blocking shutdown indefinitely, which would\n149:         block Cloud Run's revision termination and trigger\n150:         ``container did not stop in time`` SIGKILL anyway.\n151:         \"\"\"\n152:         if self._flusher_task is None:\n153:             return\n154:         self._stopping.set()\n155:         self._wake_event.set()  # break the loop's wait immediately\n156:         try:\n157:             await asyncio.wait_for(self._flusher_task, timeout=timeout)\n158:         except TimeoutError:\n159:             logger.warning(\n160:                 \"audit queue flusher did not drain within %ss; cancelling\",\n161:                 timeout,\n162:             )\n163:             self._flusher_task.cancel()\n164:             try:\n165:                 await self._flusher_task\n166:             except (asyncio.CancelledError, Exception):\n167:                 pass\n168:         finally:\n169:             self._flusher_task = None\n170: \n171:     async def _flusher_loop(self) -> None:\n172:         \"\"\"Wake on threshold OR interval, drain available events, flush.\"\"\"\n173:         while not self._stopping.is_set():\n174:             try:\n175:                 # Wait for either the threshold-wake event or the\n176:                 # interval timer, whichever fires first. ``wait_for``\n177:                 # propagates ``TimeoutError`` on the interval path; we\n178:                 # catch it and treat as a normal \"interval flush\" tick.\n179:                 try:\n180:                     await asyncio.wait_for(self._wake_event.wait(), timeout=self._flush_interval)\n181:                 except TimeoutError:\n182:                     pass\n183:                 self._wake_event.clear()\n184:                 await self._drain_and_flush()\n185:             except Exception:\n186:                 # ``_drain_and_flush`` catches per-chunk flush failures\n187:                 # internally (logs + bumps ``_failed_count``) so this\n188:                 # ``except`` only fires on genuinely unexpected errors\n189:                 # — queue corruption, an asyncio internal bug, etc. —\n190:                 # not on transient storage-api blips. The loop must\n191:                 # still survive those, since the alternative is silent\n192:                 # audit ingestion stop.\n193:                 logger.exception(\"audit flush iteration failed unexpectedly; continuing\")\n194: \n195:         # Final drain on shutdown — best-effort, bounded by stop()'s\n196:         # outer timeout.\n197:         try:\n198:             await self._drain_and_flush()\n199:         except Exception:\n200:             logger.exception(\"audit shutdown flush failed\")\n201: \n202:     async def _drain_and_flush(self) -> None:\n203:         \"\"\"Drain the queue, then flush in ``chunk_size`` slices.\n204: \n205:         Slicing protects against two failure modes that a single-call\n206:         flush exposes:\n207: \n208:         1. Storage-side hard caps: ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` rejects\n209:            batches above ``_MAX_BATCH_SIZE`` (500). Without slicing, a\n210:            queue that built up past 500 (storage-api outage,\n211:            tenant-A-storm pile-up) would have its entire drained\n212:            backlog rejected on the first recovery flush.\n213:         2. Per-chunk failure isolation: a bad chunk (one transient\n214:            5xx, one bad event after future relaxations) doesn't take\n215:            down the rest of the drain. Each chunk's success/failure\n216:            is counted independently in ``_flushed_count`` /\n217:            ``_failed_count``.\n218: \n219:         Failed chunks are NOT requeued — the closure's failure log\n220:         carries enough detail for an operator to correlate the loss\n221:         with the upstream cause; requeuing would risk an infinite\n222:         retry loop on a sustained outage.\n223: \n224:         ``task_done()`` is intentionally NOT called here. The\n225:         documented ``asyncio.Queue.join()`` contract is \"wait until\n226:         all enqueued items have been processed\" — calling\n227:         ``task_done()`` before the flush would let ``join()`` return\n228:         while events were still buffered in ``events`` and not yet\n229:         written to storage. Nothing in the codebase calls\n230:         ``queue.join()`` today; if a future caller wires it for a\n231:         stricter drain semantic, the right place for ``task_done()``\n232:         is after the per-chunk flush completes successfully (or\n233:         explicitly fails). Today's shutdown path uses ``stop()`` +\n234:         the final ``_drain_and_flush`` call, which doesn't depend on\n235:         the unfinished-task counter at all.\n236:         \"\"\"\n237:         events: list[dict] = []\n238:         while True:\n239:             try:\n240:                 events.append(self._queue.get_nowait())\n241:             except asyncio.QueueEmpty:\n242:                 break\n243:         if not events:\n244:             return\n245:         for i in range(0, len(events), self._chunk_size):\n246:             chunk = events[i : i + self._chunk_size]\n247:             try:\n248:                 await self._flush_callable(chunk)\n249:                 self._flushed_count += len(chunk)\n250:                 # CAURA-631: callables that drop sentinel events (e.g. audit\n251:                 # events without ``tenant_id``) stash the dropped count on\n252:                 # themselves so we don't silently credit them as flushed.\n253:                 # Defaults to 0 for callables that don't use this protocol.\n254:                 self._flushed_count -= getattr(self._flush_callable, \"_sentinel_count\", 0)\n255:             except BaseException as exc:\n256:                 # CAURA-631: when the callable handles per-tenant flushes\n257:                 # and only some sub-groups fail, it sets ``failed_event_count``\n258:                 # on the raised exception so we credit the actually-failed\n259:                 # events to ``_failed_count`` and the rest to\n260:                 # ``_flushed_count``. Falls back to ``len(chunk)`` for\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 338. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"In-memory audit-event queue + background batched flusher (CAURA-628).\n\nPre-CAURA-628 every memory write triggered a fire-and-forget background\ntask that POSTed one audit event to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk\nstorms (100-item batches x tenant A's 20-concurrent storm = up to 2000\naudit POSTs in flight) those calls saturated the storage-api per-tenant\nslot AND piled up on the AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock,\nqueueing tenant B's gentle audit traffic behind tenant A's fan-out.\nThat cross-tenant queueing is the residual contention the CAURA-627\ndeep-dive identified as the dominant remaining ``noisy-neighbor-write``\ncause, after the LLM-pool fix in #34 and the dead-index drop in #35.\n\nThis module replaces the per-event POST with an in-memory ``asyncio``\nqueue + a background flusher that batches events and writes them to a\nnew ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` endpoint. Flush triggers are first-of:\n\n  - ``audit_queue_flush_threshold`` events accumulated (50 by default)\n  - ``audit_queue_flush_interval_seconds`` elapsed since last flush (1s)\n\nPer-event memory overhead is small (~200 bytes for an audit dict at the","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_queue.py","text":"\"\"\"In-memory audit-event queue + background batched flusher (CAURA-628).\n\nPre-CAURA-628 every memory write triggered a fire-and-forget background\ntask that POSTed one audit event to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk\nstorms (100-item batches x tenant A's 20-concurrent storm = up to 2000\naudit POSTs in flight) those calls saturated the storage-api per-tenant\nslot AND piled up on the AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock,\nqueueing tenant B's gentle audit traffic behind tenant A's fan-out.\nThat cross-tenant queueing is the residual contention the CAURA-627\ndeep-dive identified as the dominant remaining ``noisy-neighbor-write``\ncause, after the LLM-pool fix in #34 and the dead-index drop in #35.\n\nThis module replaces the per-event POST with an in-memory ``asyncio``\nqueue + a background flusher that batches events and writes them to a\nnew ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` endpoint. Flush triggers are first-of:\n\n  - ``audit_queue_flush_threshold`` events accumulated (50 by default)\n  - ``audit_queue_flush_interval_seconds`` elapsed since last flush (1s)\n\nPer-event memory overhead is small (~200 bytes for an audit dict at the\ndefault sizes), so a 10000-event cap fits in ~2 MiB per worker process —\nplenty of headroom over the realistic worst-case storm rate.\n\nBackpressure: the queue is bounded. If writers fill the queue faster\nthan the flusher drains it (storage-api degraded, or a sustained burst\nlarger than the cap), new events are dropped with a structured warning\ncounter rather than blocking the request hot path. Audit is not on the\ncritical correctness path; loss of a few events under sustained\noverload is preferable to defeating the whole point of async ingestion\nby blocking writers.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport asyncio\nimport logging\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nclass AuditEventQueue:\n    \"\"\"Bounded in-memory queue for audit events with a background flusher.\n\n    Lifecycle: ``start()`` from FastAPI lifespan startup,\n    ``stop(timeout=...)`` from shutdown. Both are idempotent so a\n    re-import in tests doesn't double-start the task.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(\n        self,\n        *,\n        max_queue_size: int,\n        flush_threshold: int,\n        flush_interval_seconds: float,\n        flush_callable,  # async (events: list[dict]) -> None\n        chunk_size: int = 500,\n    ) -> None:\n        self._max_queue_size = max_queue_size\n        self._flush_threshold = flush_threshold\n        self._flush_interval = flush_interval_seconds\n        self._flush_callable = flush_callable\n        # ``chunk_size`` caps the per-call batch given to ``flush_callable``.\n        # The storage-side ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` endpoint enforces\n        # ``_MAX_BATCH_SIZE = 500``; if the queue ever holds more than\n        # that (e.g. storage-api was degraded and the queue built up),\n        # a single uncapped flush would 422 and lose every drained\n        # event. Slicing the drained list into chunks keeps each flush\n        # call within the storage cap, and per-chunk failure isolation\n        # means a bad chunk doesn't take down the rest of the drain.\n        # Default matches the storage-side cap exactly; tests pass\n        # ``chunk_size=1`` to exercise the slicing path without\n        # depending on the storage-side constant.\n        self._chunk_size = chunk_size\n        self._queue: asyncio.Queue[dict] = asyncio.Queue(maxsize=max_queue_size)\n        self._flusher_task: asyncio.Task[None] | None = None\n        self._stopping = asyncio.Event()\n        self._dropped_count = 0\n        self._flushed_count = 0\n        self._failed_count = 0\n        self._wake_event = asyncio.Event()  # set when threshold reached\n\n    @property\n    def dropped_count(self) -> int:\n        \"\"\"Events rejected at enqueue time because the queue was full.\"\"\"\n        return self._dropped_count\n\n    @property\n    def flushed_count(self) -> int:\n        \"\"\"Events successfully written via the flush callable.\"\"\"\n        return self._flushed_count\n\n    @property\n    def failed_count(self) -> int:\n        \"\"\"Events drained from the queue but lost when the flush callable\n        raised. Distinct from ``dropped_count`` (full-queue rejection)\n        so an operator can distinguish \"writers outpacing the flusher\"\n        from \"storage-api failing the write\" in dashboards.\"\"\"\n        return self._failed_count\n\n    @property\n    def queue_size(self) -> int:\n        return self._queue.qsize()\n\n    def enqueue(self, event: dict) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Non-blocking enqueue. Drops + warns when the queue is full.\n\n        Synchronous (no ``await``) so callers in fire-and-forget paths\n        don't pay an extra event-loop hop. ``Queue.put_nowait`` returns\n        immediately when there's room; raises ``QueueFull`` otherwise,\n        which we map to a counter + structured warning rather than\n        propagating to the caller (audit isn't on the correctness\n        path; dropping is preferable to blocking the request).\n        \"\"\"\n        try:\n            self._queue.put_nowait(event)\n        except asyncio.QueueFull:\n            self._dropped_count += 1\n            # Log every 100th drop so a sustained overload produces a\n            # finite, informative log volume rather than one line per\n            # dropped event. A single first-drop line still surfaces\n            # immediately so the issue is visible.\n            if self._dropped_count == 1 or self._dropped_count % 100 == 0:\n                logger.warning(\n                    \"audit queue full; dropped %d events so far \"\n                    \"(max_queue_size=%d, flush behind storage-api?)\",\n                    self._dropped_count,\n                    self._max_queue_size,\n                )\n            return\n        # Wake the flusher early when we reach the batch threshold so a\n        # storm doesn't have to wait for the interval timer.\n        if self._queue.qsize() >= self._flush_threshold:\n            self._wake_event.set()\n\n    async def start(self) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Idempotent: a second call is a no-op.\"\"\"\n        if self._flusher_task is not None and not self._flusher_task.done():\n            return\n        self._stopping.clear()\n        self._flusher_task = asyncio.create_task(self._flusher_loop(), name=\"audit-queue-flusher\")\n\n    async def stop(self, *, timeout: float = 5.0) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Signal the flusher to drain pending events and exit.\n\n        Waits up to ``timeout`` seconds for the final flush. If the\n        deadline expires (storage-api hung), the flusher task is\n        cancelled and any still-in-queue events are lost — the\n        alternative is blocking shutdown indefinitely, which would\n        block Cloud Run's revision termination and trigger\n        ``container did not stop in time`` SIGKILL anyway.\n        \"\"\"\n        if self._flusher_task is None:\n            return\n        self._stopping.set()\n        self._wake_event.set()  # break the loop's wait immediately\n        try:\n            await asyncio.wait_for(self._flusher_task, timeout=timeout)\n        except TimeoutError:\n            logger.warning(\n                \"audit queue flusher did not drain within %ss; cancelling\",\n                timeout,\n            )\n            self._flusher_task.cancel()\n            try:\n                await self._flusher_task\n            except (asyncio.CancelledError, Exception):\n                pass\n        finally:\n            self._flusher_task = None\n\n    async def _flusher_loop(self) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Wake on threshold OR interval, drain available events, flush.\"\"\"\n        while not self._stopping.is_set():\n            try:\n                # Wait for either the threshold-wake event or the\n                # interval timer, whichever fires first. ``wait_for``\n                # propagates ``TimeoutError`` on the interval path; we\n                # catch it and treat as a normal \"interval flush\" tick.\n                try:\n                    await asyncio.wait_for(self._wake_event.wait(), timeout=self._flush_interval)\n                except TimeoutError:\n                    pass\n                self._wake_event.clear()\n                await self._drain_and_flush()\n            except Exception:\n                # ``_drain_and_flush`` catches per-chunk flush failures\n                # internally (logs + bumps ``_failed_count``) so this\n                # ``except`` only fires on genuinely unexpected errors\n                # — queue corruption, an asyncio internal bug, etc. —\n                # not on transient storage-api blips. The loop must\n                # still survive those, since the alternative is silent\n                # audit ingestion stop.\n                logger.exception(\"audit flush iteration failed unexpectedly; continuing\")\n\n        # Final drain on shutdown — best-effort, bounded by stop()'s\n        # outer timeout.\n        try:\n            await self._drain_and_flush()\n        except Exception:\n            logger.exception(\"audit shutdown flush failed\")\n\n    async def _drain_and_flush(self) -> None:\n        \"\"\"Drain the queue, then flush in ``chunk_size`` slices.\n\n        Slicing protects against two failure modes that a single-call\n        flush exposes:\n\n        1. Storage-side hard caps: ``POST /audit-logs/bulk`` rejects\n           batches above ``_MAX_BATCH_SIZE`` (500). Without slicing, a\n           queue that built up past 500 (storage-api outage,\n           tenant-A-storm pile-up) would have its entire drained\n           backlog rejected on the first recovery flush.\n        2. Per-chunk failure isolation: a bad chunk (one transient\n           5xx, one bad event after future relaxations) doesn't take\n           down the rest of the drain. Each chunk's success/failure\n           is counted independently in ``_flushed_count`` /\n           ``_failed_count``.\n\n        Failed chunks are NOT requeued — the closure's failure log\n        carries enough detail for an operator to correlate the loss\n        with the upstream cause; requeuing would risk an infinite\n        retry loop on a sustained outage.\n\n        ``task_done()`` is intentionally NOT called here. The\n        documented ``asyncio.Queue.join()`` contract is \"wait until\n        all enqueued items have been processed\" — calling\n        ``task_done()`` before the flush would let ``join()`` return\n        while events were still buffered in ``events`` and not yet\n        written to storage. Nothing in the codebase calls\n        ``queue.join()`` today; if a future caller wires it for a\n        stricter drain semantic, the right place for ``task_done()``\n        is after the per-chunk flush completes successfully (or\n        explicitly fails). Today's shutdown path uses ``stop()`` +\n        the final ``_drain_and_flush`` call, which doesn't depend on\n        the unfinished-task counter at all.\n        \"\"\"\n        events: list[dict] = []\n        while True:\n            try:\n                events.append(self._queue.get_nowait())\n            except asyncio.QueueEmpty:\n                break\n        if not events:\n            return\n        for i in range(0, len(events), self._chunk_size):\n            chunk = events[i : i + self._chunk_size]\n            try:\n                await self._flush_callable(chunk)\n                self._flushed_count += len(chunk)\n                # CAURA-631: callables that drop sentinel events (e.g. audit\n                # events without ``tenant_id``) stash the dropped count on\n                # themselves so we don't silently credit them as flushed.\n                # Defaults to 0 for callables that don't use this protocol.\n                self._flushed_count -= getattr(self._flush_callable, \"_sentinel_count\", 0)\n            except BaseException as exc:\n                # CAURA-631: when the callable handles per-tenant flushes\n                # and only some sub-groups fail, it sets ``failed_event_count``\n                # on the raised exception so we credit the actually-failed\n                # events to ``_failed_count`` and the rest to\n                # ``_flushed_count``. Falls back to ``len(chunk)`` for","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":260,"totalLines":338,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_queue.py","time":{"start":1780727723714,"end":1780727723717}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cc08191b1b6377023e1b612"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6b6001YwX534AQwTR2e8","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723732,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cC0mnCsUaigJXtLsNYqgcgCk","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Boundary guard for soft-deleted org tenants (CAURA-694).\n2: \n3: When an enterprise org is soft-deleted, ``platform-admin-api`` publishes\n4: ``memclaw.org.suppression-changed`` with the list of tenant_ids the\n5: action covers. Core-worker mirrors that into\n6: ``public.tenant_suppression`` (CAURA-694 storage migration). This module\n7: is the synchronous read side: core-api's auth layer asks\n8: :func:`is_tenant_suppressed` on every authenticated request and 403s\n9: when the answer is ``True``.\n10: \n11: Why a short TTL cache:\n12: \n13:   - core-api authenticates **every** request — on the recall / read /\n14:     write paths that's the hottest dependency we own. A storage\n15:     round-trip per request would double request-side latency.\n16:   - The TTL bound (30 s) is the same shape the auth-api uses for the\n17:     enterprise org-deleted check (CAURA-690): operators who soft-delete\n18:     an org accept up to that much latency on the access cut-off, in\n19:     exchange for the per-request cost. The synchronous auth-api gate\n20:     (CAURA-690) already blocks JWT/cookie/API-key login paths immediately;\n21:     this cache only governs the in-flight request window for callers who\n22:     bypass auth-api (raw API-key path, OSS standalone).\n23: \n24: Fail-open on transport error: a storage outage MUST NOT 403 every\n25: request — the alternative is a self-inflicted DOS of core-api on\n26: storage flaps. We log the failure and treat the tenant as live until\n27: the cache window expires. The keystone-quality guarantee is therefore\n28: \"suppressed-tenant requests are blocked, **modulo a brief window on\n29: storage outage**\" — acceptable because the durable hard-delete sweep\n30: (CAURA-691 / -692) and the auth-api gate (CAURA-690) are the real\n31: defence-in-depth lines.\n32: \"\"\"\n33: \n34: from __future__ import annotations\n35: \n36: import logging\n37: import time\n38: \n39: from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n40: \n41: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n42: \n43: # Mirror the auth-api ``_is_org_deleted`` cache window (CAURA-690).\n44: # Operators who soft-delete an org accept up to this much latency on\n45: # the access cut-off, and the synchronous auth-api gate already covers\n46: # the user-facing login flow — this cache only governs the bypass paths\n47: # (raw API-key, OSS standalone) within the window.\n48: _TTL_SECONDS: float = 30.0\n49: \n50: # Shorter TTL written on storage failure (PR #244 bot review round 1,\n51: # 🟠 High). Without this, the failure path returned ``False`` WITHOUT\n52: # writing to the cache, so every subsequent authenticated request hit\n53: # storage again during an outage — a thundering herd that turns a\n54: # brief blip into a self-amplifying retry storm. 5 s gives the cache\n55: # time to absorb the load while still self-healing fast once storage\n56: # recovers (vs. waiting the full 30 s success-TTL).\n57: _ERROR_TTL_SECONDS: float = 5.0\n58: \n59: # Module-level cache: ``{tenant_id: (is_suppressed, monotonic_expires_at)}``.\n60: # A dict is cheap; entries are evicted on write (see ``_prune_expired``\n61: # below) so a long-running process with high tenant turnover doesn't\n62: # leak memory by accumulating expired keys forever. Bot review round 2\n63: # on PR #244.\n64: _cache: dict[str, tuple[bool, float]] = {}\n65: \n66: \n67: def _prune_expired(now: float) -> None:\n68:     \"\"\"Drop ``_cache`` entries whose TTL has passed.\n69: \n70:     Called immediately before each write so the per-call cost is\n71:     proportional to the number of currently-cached tenants (bounded\n72:     by distinct tenants seen in the last ``_TTL_SECONDS`` window) and\n73:     expired keys never linger. Building the key list before mutating\n74:     avoids \"dictionary changed size during iteration\" — Python doesn't\n75:     allow ``pop`` during ``items()`` traversal.\n76:     \"\"\"\n77:     expired = [tid for tid, (_, exp) in _cache.items() if exp <= now]\n78:     for tid in expired:\n79:         _cache.pop(tid, None)\n80: \n81: \n82: def reset_cache_for_testing() -> None:\n83:     \"\"\"Clear the cache. Test-only — never call from production code.\"\"\"\n84:     _cache.clear()\n85: \n86: \n87: async def is_tenant_suppressed(tenant_id: str) -> bool:\n88:     \"\"\"Cached check: is this tenant currently soft-deleted?\n89: \n90:     Returns ``True`` only on a confirmed-suppressed answer. Any other\n91:     case (live, unknown, transport failure) returns ``False`` — the\n92:     boundary fails OPEN so a storage flap can't take core-api down.\n93:     \"\"\"\n94:     now = time.monotonic()\n95:     cached = _cache.get(tenant_id)\n96:     if cached is not None and cached[1] > now:\n97:         return cached[0]\n98: \n99:     try:\n100:         suppressed = await get_storage_client().is_tenant_suppressed(tenant_id)\n101:     except Exception:\n102:         # Fail open. Log but DO NOT block the request — see module\n103:         # docstring for the trade-off.\n104:         #\n105:         # Cache the ``False`` result with the SHORT error-TTL so we\n106:         # don't hammer storage on every subsequent request during an\n107:         # outage. Bot review round 1 on PR #244 (🟠 High): without\n108:         # the cache write, a brief storage blip became a self-amplifying\n109:         # retry storm across every authenticated request. 5 s lets the\n110:         # cache absorb the load and still self-heal quickly once\n111:         # storage recovers (vs. the 30 s success-TTL).\n112:         logger.warning(\n113:             \"tenant suppression check failed; failing open\",\n114:             extra={\"tenant_id\": tenant_id},\n115:             exc_info=True,\n116:         )\n117:         _prune_expired(now)\n118:         _cache[tenant_id] = (False, now + _ERROR_TTL_SECONDS)\n119:         return False\n120: \n121:     _prune_expired(now)\n122:     _cache[tenant_id] = (suppressed, now + _TTL_SECONDS)\n123:     return suppressed\n\n(End of file - total 123 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Boundary guard for soft-deleted org tenants (CAURA-694).\n\nWhen an enterprise org is soft-deleted, ``platform-admin-api`` publishes\n``memclaw.org.suppression-changed`` with the list of tenant_ids the\naction covers. Core-worker mirrors that into\n``public.tenant_suppression`` (CAURA-694 storage migration). This module\nis the synchronous read side: core-api's auth layer asks\n:func:`is_tenant_suppressed` on every authenticated request and 403s\nwhen the answer is ``True``.\n\nWhy a short TTL cache:\n\n  - core-api authenticates **every** request — on the recall / read /\n    write paths that's the hottest dependency we own. A storage\n    round-trip per request would double request-side latency.\n  - The TTL bound (30 s) is the same shape the auth-api uses for the\n    enterprise org-deleted check (CAURA-690): operators who soft-delete\n    an org accept up to that much latency on the access cut-off, in\n    exchange for the per-request cost. The synchronous auth-api gate\n    (CAURA-690) already blocks JWT/cookie/API-key login paths immediately;","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py","text":"\"\"\"Boundary guard for soft-deleted org tenants (CAURA-694).\n\nWhen an enterprise org is soft-deleted, ``platform-admin-api`` publishes\n``memclaw.org.suppression-changed`` with the list of tenant_ids the\naction covers. Core-worker mirrors that into\n``public.tenant_suppression`` (CAURA-694 storage migration). This module\nis the synchronous read side: core-api's auth layer asks\n:func:`is_tenant_suppressed` on every authenticated request and 403s\nwhen the answer is ``True``.\n\nWhy a short TTL cache:\n\n  - core-api authenticates **every** request — on the recall / read /\n    write paths that's the hottest dependency we own. A storage\n    round-trip per request would double request-side latency.\n  - The TTL bound (30 s) is the same shape the auth-api uses for the\n    enterprise org-deleted check (CAURA-690): operators who soft-delete\n    an org accept up to that much latency on the access cut-off, in\n    exchange for the per-request cost. The synchronous auth-api gate\n    (CAURA-690) already blocks JWT/cookie/API-key login paths immediately;\n    this cache only governs the in-flight request window for callers who\n    bypass auth-api (raw API-key path, OSS standalone).\n\nFail-open on transport error: a storage outage MUST NOT 403 every\nrequest — the alternative is a self-inflicted DOS of core-api on\nstorage flaps. We log the failure and treat the tenant as live until\nthe cache window expires. The keystone-quality guarantee is therefore\n\"suppressed-tenant requests are blocked, **modulo a brief window on\nstorage outage**\" — acceptable because the durable hard-delete sweep\n(CAURA-691 / -692) and the auth-api gate (CAURA-690) are the real\ndefence-in-depth lines.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\nimport time\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n# Mirror the auth-api ``_is_org_deleted`` cache window (CAURA-690).\n# Operators who soft-delete an org accept up to this much latency on\n# the access cut-off, and the synchronous auth-api gate already covers\n# the user-facing login flow — this cache only governs the bypass paths\n# (raw API-key, OSS standalone) within the window.\n_TTL_SECONDS: float = 30.0\n\n# Shorter TTL written on storage failure (PR #244 bot review round 1,\n# 🟠 High). Without this, the failure path returned ``False`` WITHOUT\n# writing to the cache, so every subsequent authenticated request hit\n# storage again during an outage — a thundering herd that turns a\n# brief blip into a self-amplifying retry storm. 5 s gives the cache\n# time to absorb the load while still self-healing fast once storage\n# recovers (vs. waiting the full 30 s success-TTL).\n_ERROR_TTL_SECONDS: float = 5.0\n\n# Module-level cache: ``{tenant_id: (is_suppressed, monotonic_expires_at)}``.\n# A dict is cheap; entries are evicted on write (see ``_prune_expired``\n# below) so a long-running process with high tenant turnover doesn't\n# leak memory by accumulating expired keys forever. Bot review round 2\n# on PR #244.\n_cache: dict[str, tuple[bool, float]] = {}\n\n\ndef _prune_expired(now: float) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Drop ``_cache`` entries whose TTL has passed.\n\n    Called immediately before each write so the per-call cost is\n    proportional to the number of currently-cached tenants (bounded\n    by distinct tenants seen in the last ``_TTL_SECONDS`` window) and\n    expired keys never linger. Building the key list before mutating\n    avoids \"dictionary changed size during iteration\" — Python doesn't\n    allow ``pop`` during ``items()`` traversal.\n    \"\"\"\n    expired = [tid for tid, (_, exp) in _cache.items() if exp <= now]\n    for tid in expired:\n        _cache.pop(tid, None)\n\n\ndef reset_cache_for_testing() -> None:\n    \"\"\"Clear the cache. Test-only — never call from production code.\"\"\"\n    _cache.clear()\n\n\nasync def is_tenant_suppressed(tenant_id: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Cached check: is this tenant currently soft-deleted?\n\n    Returns ``True`` only on a confirmed-suppressed answer. Any other\n    case (live, unknown, transport failure) returns ``False`` — the\n    boundary fails OPEN so a storage flap can't take core-api down.\n    \"\"\"\n    now = time.monotonic()\n    cached = _cache.get(tenant_id)\n    if cached is not None and cached[1] > now:\n        return cached[0]\n\n    try:\n        suppressed = await get_storage_client().is_tenant_suppressed(tenant_id)\n    except Exception:\n        # Fail open. Log but DO NOT block the request — see module\n        # docstring for the trade-off.\n        #\n        # Cache the ``False`` result with the SHORT error-TTL so we\n        # don't hammer storage on every subsequent request during an\n        # outage. Bot review round 1 on PR #244 (🟠 High): without\n        # the cache write, a brief storage blip became a self-amplifying\n        # retry storm across every authenticated request. 5 s lets the\n        # cache absorb the load and still self-heal quickly once\n        # storage recovers (vs. the 30 s success-TTL).\n        logger.warning(\n            \"tenant suppression check failed; failing open\",\n            extra={\"tenant_id\": tenant_id},\n            exc_info=True,\n        )\n        _prune_expired(now)\n        _cache[tenant_id] = (False, now + _ERROR_TTL_SECONDS)\n        return False\n\n    _prune_expired(now)\n    _cache[tenant_id] = (suppressed, now + _TTL_SECONDS)\n    return suppressed","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":123,"totalLines":123,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py","time":{"start":1780727723723,"end":1780727723731}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cc48191a5579ab8b2afc2cd"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6c3001nKN9RBMtA1RnP7","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723733,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_njMtqTI8BUUpyLNE378sZbBP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/tenant_suppression.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/tenant_suppression.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Tenant suppression mirror (CAURA-694).\n2: \n3: Stores one row per tenant the enterprise org-lifecycle has ever\n4: touched. Two endpoints:\n5: \n6:   - ``POST /tenant-suppression`` — upsert for the OSS suppression\n7:     consumer (core-worker in SaaS, core-api in OSS-standalone if it\n8:     grows a subscriber). Body: ``{tenant_id, action, updated_by?}``\n9:     where ``action`` is ``suppress`` | ``restore``.\n10:   - ``GET  /tenant-suppression/{tenant_id}`` — boundary-guard read.\n11:     Returns ``{tenant_id, suppressed_at, updated_at, updated_by}`` or\n12:     a small ``{tenant_id, suppressed_at: null}`` for an unknown\n13:     tenant. Hot path — kept light so core-api can call it on every\n14:     authenticated request behind a small in-process cache.\n15: \n16: Same trust model as the rest of core-storage-api (see\n17: ``routers/purge.py``): no router-level authentication; the deployment\n18: runs storage on a VPC-internal endpoint and trusts upstream auth at\n19: core-api. Do NOT expose this surface to the public internet.\n20: \"\"\"\n21: \n22: from __future__ import annotations\n23: \n24: import json\n25: from typing import Literal\n26: \n27: from fastapi import APIRouter, HTTPException, Request\n28: \n29: from core_storage_api.services.postgres_service import PostgresService\n30: \n31: router = APIRouter(prefix=\"/tenant-suppression\", tags=[\"TenantSuppression\"])\n32: _svc = PostgresService()\n33: \n34: \n35: # Pydantic would be overkill for a two-field body; we validate inline\n36: # to stay consistent with ``routers/purge.py``.\n37: _ALLOWED_ACTIONS: set[str] = {\"suppress\", \"restore\"}\n38: \n39: \n40: @router.post(\"\")\n41: async def upsert_tenant_suppression(request: Request) -> dict:\n42:     \"\"\"Upsert one row. Body: ``{tenant_id, action, updated_by?}``.\n43: \n44:     Returns the resulting row so the caller can log the post-state\n45:     without an extra GET. The service-layer ``set_tenant_suppression``\n46:     is the single SQL source of truth for the ``suppress`` /\n47:     ``restore`` semantics — this router only validates the wire\n48:     contract.\n49:     \"\"\"\n50:     try:\n51:         body = await request.json()\n52:     except (json.JSONDecodeError, UnicodeDecodeError) as exc:\n53:         # ``UnicodeDecodeError`` fires when the request body contains\n54:         # invalid UTF-8 bytes — distinct from ``JSONDecodeError`` and\n55:         # NOT a subclass of it, so a single-class catch missed it and\n56:         # surfaced as 500. Bot review round 1 on PR #244 (🟢 Low).\n57:         raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"request body must be valid JSON\") from exc\n58:     # A valid JSON body can also be an array / number / string — calling\n59:     # ``.get`` on those raises ``AttributeError`` and 500s. Bot review\n60:     # round 1 on PR #244 (🟡 Med).\n61:     if not isinstance(body, dict):\n62:         raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"request body must be a JSON object\")\n63:     tenant_id = body.get(\"tenant_id\")\n64:     action = body.get(\"action\")\n65:     updated_by = body.get(\"updated_by\")\n66:     if not isinstance(tenant_id, str) or not tenant_id:\n67:         raise HTTPException(\n68:             status_code=422,\n69:             detail=\"'tenant_id' is required and must be a non-empty string\",\n70:         )\n71:     if action not in _ALLOWED_ACTIONS:\n72:         raise HTTPException(\n73:             status_code=422,\n74:             detail=f\"'action' must be one of {sorted(_ALLOWED_ACTIONS)!r}\",\n75:         )\n76:     # ``updated_by`` is optional; reject non-string values for the same\n77:     # reason ``tenant_id`` rejects them — silent coercion of an int /\n78:     # dict to ``str()`` masks an upstream bug.\n79:     if updated_by is not None and not isinstance(updated_by, str):\n80:         raise HTTPException(\n81:             status_code=422,\n82:             detail=\"'updated_by' must be a string when provided\",\n83:         )\n84:     typed_action: Literal[\"suppress\", \"restore\"] = action  # narrowed above\n85:     row = await _svc.set_tenant_suppression(tenant_id, action=typed_action, updated_by=updated_by)\n86:     return row\n87: \n88: \n89: @router.get(\"/{tenant_id}\")\n90: async def get_tenant_suppression(tenant_id: str) -> dict:\n91:     \"\"\"Boundary-guard read. Returns ``{tenant_id, is_suppressed}``.\n92: \n93:     A separate, intentionally-shallow shape from the full row returned\n94:     by the POST: the boundary guard only ever asks \"is this tenant\n95:     suppressed right now?\" — surfacing the full row here would invite\n96:     consumers to start depending on ``updated_at`` and erode the cache\n97:     invariant. A missing row is the same as \"not suppressed\", which is\n98:     the standalone-OSS shape.\n99:     \"\"\"\n100:     suppressed = await _svc.is_tenant_suppressed(tenant_id)\n101:     return {\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"is_suppressed\": suppressed}\n\n(End of file - total 101 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Tenant suppression mirror (CAURA-694).\n\nStores one row per tenant the enterprise org-lifecycle has ever\ntouched. Two endpoints:\n\n  - ``POST /tenant-suppression`` — upsert for the OSS suppression\n    consumer (core-worker in SaaS, core-api in OSS-standalone if it\n    grows a subscriber). Body: ``{tenant_id, action, updated_by?}``\n    where ``action`` is ``suppress`` | ``restore``.\n  - ``GET  /tenant-suppression/{tenant_id}`` — boundary-guard read.\n    Returns ``{tenant_id, suppressed_at, updated_at, updated_by}`` or\n    a small ``{tenant_id, suppressed_at: null}`` for an unknown\n    tenant. Hot path — kept light so core-api can call it on every\n    authenticated request behind a small in-process cache.\n\nSame trust model as the rest of core-storage-api (see\n``routers/purge.py``): no router-level authentication; the deployment\nruns storage on a VPC-internal endpoint and trusts upstream auth at\ncore-api. Do NOT expose this surface to the public internet.\n\"\"\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/tenant_suppression.py","text":"\"\"\"Tenant suppression mirror (CAURA-694).\n\nStores one row per tenant the enterprise org-lifecycle has ever\ntouched. Two endpoints:\n\n  - ``POST /tenant-suppression`` — upsert for the OSS suppression\n    consumer (core-worker in SaaS, core-api in OSS-standalone if it\n    grows a subscriber). Body: ``{tenant_id, action, updated_by?}``\n    where ``action`` is ``suppress`` | ``restore``.\n  - ``GET  /tenant-suppression/{tenant_id}`` — boundary-guard read.\n    Returns ``{tenant_id, suppressed_at, updated_at, updated_by}`` or\n    a small ``{tenant_id, suppressed_at: null}`` for an unknown\n    tenant. Hot path — kept light so core-api can call it on every\n    authenticated request behind a small in-process cache.\n\nSame trust model as the rest of core-storage-api (see\n``routers/purge.py``): no router-level authentication; the deployment\nruns storage on a VPC-internal endpoint and trusts upstream auth at\ncore-api. Do NOT expose this surface to the public internet.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport json\nfrom typing import Literal\n\nfrom fastapi import APIRouter, HTTPException, Request\n\nfrom core_storage_api.services.postgres_service import PostgresService\n\nrouter = APIRouter(prefix=\"/tenant-suppression\", tags=[\"TenantSuppression\"])\n_svc = PostgresService()\n\n\n# Pydantic would be overkill for a two-field body; we validate inline\n# to stay consistent with ``routers/purge.py``.\n_ALLOWED_ACTIONS: set[str] = {\"suppress\", \"restore\"}\n\n\n@router.post(\"\")\nasync def upsert_tenant_suppression(request: Request) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Upsert one row. Body: ``{tenant_id, action, updated_by?}``.\n\n    Returns the resulting row so the caller can log the post-state\n    without an extra GET. The service-layer ``set_tenant_suppression``\n    is the single SQL source of truth for the ``suppress`` /\n    ``restore`` semantics — this router only validates the wire\n    contract.\n    \"\"\"\n    try:\n        body = await request.json()\n    except (json.JSONDecodeError, UnicodeDecodeError) as exc:\n        # ``UnicodeDecodeError`` fires when the request body contains\n        # invalid UTF-8 bytes — distinct from ``JSONDecodeError`` and\n        # NOT a subclass of it, so a single-class catch missed it and\n        # surfaced as 500. Bot review round 1 on PR #244 (🟢 Low).\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"request body must be valid JSON\") from exc\n    # A valid JSON body can also be an array / number / string — calling\n    # ``.get`` on those raises ``AttributeError`` and 500s. Bot review\n    # round 1 on PR #244 (🟡 Med).\n    if not isinstance(body, dict):\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"request body must be a JSON object\")\n    tenant_id = body.get(\"tenant_id\")\n    action = body.get(\"action\")\n    updated_by = body.get(\"updated_by\")\n    if not isinstance(tenant_id, str) or not tenant_id:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=\"'tenant_id' is required and must be a non-empty string\",\n        )\n    if action not in _ALLOWED_ACTIONS:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=f\"'action' must be one of {sorted(_ALLOWED_ACTIONS)!r}\",\n        )\n    # ``updated_by`` is optional; reject non-string values for the same\n    # reason ``tenant_id`` rejects them — silent coercion of an int /\n    # dict to ``str()`` masks an upstream bug.\n    if updated_by is not None and not isinstance(updated_by, str):\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=\"'updated_by' must be a string when provided\",\n        )\n    typed_action: Literal[\"suppress\", \"restore\"] = action  # narrowed above\n    row = await _svc.set_tenant_suppression(tenant_id, action=typed_action, updated_by=updated_by)\n    return row\n\n\n@router.get(\"/{tenant_id}\")\nasync def get_tenant_suppression(tenant_id: str) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Boundary-guard read. Returns ``{tenant_id, is_suppressed}``.\n\n    A separate, intentionally-shallow shape from the full row returned\n    by the POST: the boundary guard only ever asks \"is this tenant\n    suppressed right now?\" — surfacing the full row here would invite\n    consumers to start depending on ``updated_at`` and erode the cache\n    invariant. A missing row is the same as \"not suppressed\", which is\n    the standalone-OSS shape.\n    \"\"\"\n    suppressed = await _svc.is_tenant_suppressed(tenant_id)\n    return {\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"is_suppressed\": suppressed}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":101,"totalLines":101,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/tenant_suppression.py","time":{"start":1780727723728,"end":1780727723732}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9ccc8191b538563812171c7c"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6cf001QZsNfXmDvuV5JM","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723741,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ZiFmiGL8YzeoWO6KGPeKsNVb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/models/memory.py","offset":1,"limit":180},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/models/memory.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: import uuid\n2: from datetime import datetime\n3: \n4: from pgvector.sqlalchemy import Vector\n5: from sqlalchemy import DateTime, Float, ForeignKey, Index, Integer, Text, func, text\n6: from sqlalchemy.dialects.postgresql import JSONB, TSVECTOR, UUID as PG_UUID\n7: from sqlalchemy.orm import Mapped, mapped_column\n8: \n9: from common.constants import VECTOR_DIM\n10: from common.models.base import Base\n11: \n12: \n13: class Memory(Base):\n14:     __tablename__ = \"memories\"\n15: \n16:     id: Mapped[uuid.UUID] = mapped_column(\n17:         primary_key=True, server_default=text(\"gen_random_uuid()\")\n18:     )\n19:     tenant_id: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False, index=True)\n20:     fleet_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n21:     agent_id: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False)\n22:     memory_type: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False)\n23:     content: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False)\n24:     embedding = mapped_column(Vector(VECTOR_DIM))\n25:     weight: Mapped[float] = mapped_column(Float, server_default=text(\"0.5\"))\n26:     source_uri: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n27:     run_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n28:     metadata_: Mapped[dict | None] = mapped_column(\"metadata\", JSONB)\n29:     created_at: Mapped[datetime] = mapped_column(\n30:         DateTime(timezone=True), server_default=text(\"now()\")\n31:     )\n32:     title: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n33:     content_hash: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n34:     # Per-attempt idempotency token (CAURA-602). Server-derived from\n35:     # ``X-Bulk-Attempt-Id + \":\" + index`` on the bulk path; NULL for\n36:     # single-write and pre-rollout rows. The partial unique index\n37:     # ``ix_memories_attempt_unique`` (migration 007) enforces uniqueness\n38:     # only when this is non-NULL, so legacy paths are unaffected.\n39:     client_request_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n40:     expires_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n41:     deleted_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n42:     search_vector = mapped_column(TSVECTOR)\n43: \n44:     # RDF triple representation\n45:     subject_entity_id: Mapped[uuid.UUID | None] = mapped_column(\n46:         PG_UUID(as_uuid=True),\n47:         ForeignKey(\"entities.id\", ondelete=\"SET NULL\"),\n48:     )\n49:     predicate: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n50:     object_value: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n51: \n52:     # Temporal validity windows\n53:     ts_valid_start: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n54:     ts_valid_end: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n55: \n56:     # Status lifecycle\n57:     status: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(\n58:         Text, server_default=text(\"'active'\"), nullable=False\n59:     )\n60: \n61:     # Visibility scope\n62:     visibility: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(\n63:         Text,\n64:         server_default=text(\"'scope_team'\"),\n65:         nullable=False,\n66:     )\n67: \n68:     # Recall tracking (incremented on agent-facing retrievals only)\n69:     recall_count: Mapped[int] = mapped_column(\n70:         Integer, server_default=text(\"0\"), nullable=False\n71:     )\n72:     last_recalled_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n73: \n74:     # Crystallizer dedup tracking\n75:     last_dedup_checked_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(\n76:         DateTime(timezone=True)\n77:     )\n78: \n79:     # Contradiction tracking\n80:     supersedes_id: Mapped[uuid.UUID | None] = mapped_column(\n81:         PG_UUID(as_uuid=True),\n82:         ForeignKey(\"memories.id\", ondelete=\"SET NULL\"),\n83:     )\n84: \n85:     __table_args__ = (\n86:         Index(\"ix_memories_tenant_type\", \"tenant_id\", \"memory_type\"),\n87:         Index(\"ix_memories_tenant_agent\", \"tenant_id\", \"agent_id\"),\n88:         Index(\"ix_memories_content_hash\", \"tenant_id\", \"content_hash\"),\n89:         # Backs per-attempt bulk-write idempotency (CAURA-602). Created\n90:         # ``CONCURRENTLY`` in migration 007 with the same predicates;\n91:         # declared here so SQLAlchemy reflection / Alembic autogen\n92:         # round-trips match the live schema. ``COALESCE(fleet_id, '')``\n93:         # makes fleetless rows participate in the unique constraint —\n94:         # PostgreSQL treats NULLs as distinct by default, so without\n95:         # this two retries with ``fleet_id IS NULL`` would both insert.\n96:         Index(\n97:             \"ix_memories_attempt_unique\",\n98:             \"tenant_id\",\n99:             func.coalesce(text(\"fleet_id\"), \"\"),\n100:             \"client_request_id\",\n101:             unique=True,\n102:             postgresql_where=text(\n103:                 \"deleted_at IS NULL AND client_request_id IS NOT NULL\"\n104:             ),\n105:         ),\n106:         Index(\"ix_memories_valid_range\", \"ts_valid_start\", \"ts_valid_end\"),\n107:         Index(\"ix_memories_subject_entity\", \"subject_entity_id\"),\n108:         Index(\"ix_memories_recall_count\", \"recall_count\"),\n109:         Index(\"ix_memories_tenant_fleet\", \"tenant_id\", \"fleet_id\"),\n110:         # Backs the cursor-paginated list path (``list_by_filters`` +\n111:         # the ``memclaw_list`` MCP tool) which orders by\n112:         # ``(created_at DESC, id DESC)`` under ``tenant_id = ?`` and\n113:         # ``deleted_at IS NULL``. Partial WHERE keeps the index small\n114:         # since soft-deleted rows are never read on the hot path.\n115:         # Bare-column references (``created_at.desc()`` not\n116:         # ``text(\"created_at DESC\")``) so Alembic autogen can reflect\n117:         # and compare the index — matches ``analysis_report.py:38``.\n118:         Index(\n119:             \"ix_memories_tenant_created_active\",\n120:             \"tenant_id\",\n121:             created_at.desc(),\n122:             id.desc(),\n123:             postgresql_where=text(\"deleted_at IS NULL\"),\n124:         ),\n125:         # Backs the CAURA-656 purge-fanout discovery query\n126:         # (``list_tenants_with_purgeable_memories``). Every other\n127:         # partial index on this table is keyed on\n128:         # ``deleted_at IS NULL`` (active path); without this\n129:         # complement the soft-deleted-side discovery falls back to a\n130:         # full scan.\n131:         Index(\n132:             \"ix_memories_purgeable\",\n133:             \"tenant_id\",\n134:             postgresql_where=text(\"deleted_at IS NOT NULL\"),\n135:         ),\n136:     )\n\n(End of file - total 136 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"import uuid\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\nfrom pgvector.sqlalchemy import Vector\nfrom sqlalchemy import DateTime, Float, ForeignKey, Index, Integer, Text, func, text\nfrom sqlalchemy.dialects.postgresql import JSONB, TSVECTOR, UUID as PG_UUID\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import Mapped, mapped_column\n\nfrom common.constants import VECTOR_DIM\nfrom common.models.base import Base\n\n\nclass Memory(Base):\n    __tablename__ = \"memories\"\n\n    id: Mapped[uuid.UUID] = mapped_column(\n        primary_key=True, server_default=text(\"gen_random_uuid()\")\n    )\n    tenant_id: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False, index=True)\n    fleet_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/models/memory.py","text":"import uuid\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\nfrom pgvector.sqlalchemy import Vector\nfrom sqlalchemy import DateTime, Float, ForeignKey, Index, Integer, Text, func, text\nfrom sqlalchemy.dialects.postgresql import JSONB, TSVECTOR, UUID as PG_UUID\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import Mapped, mapped_column\n\nfrom common.constants import VECTOR_DIM\nfrom common.models.base import Base\n\n\nclass Memory(Base):\n    __tablename__ = \"memories\"\n\n    id: Mapped[uuid.UUID] = mapped_column(\n        primary_key=True, server_default=text(\"gen_random_uuid()\")\n    )\n    tenant_id: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False, index=True)\n    fleet_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    agent_id: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False)\n    memory_type: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False)\n    content: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(Text, nullable=False)\n    embedding = mapped_column(Vector(VECTOR_DIM))\n    weight: Mapped[float] = mapped_column(Float, server_default=text(\"0.5\"))\n    source_uri: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    run_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    metadata_: Mapped[dict | None] = mapped_column(\"metadata\", JSONB)\n    created_at: Mapped[datetime] = mapped_column(\n        DateTime(timezone=True), server_default=text(\"now()\")\n    )\n    title: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    content_hash: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    # Per-attempt idempotency token (CAURA-602). Server-derived from\n    # ``X-Bulk-Attempt-Id + \":\" + index`` on the bulk path; NULL for\n    # single-write and pre-rollout rows. The partial unique index\n    # ``ix_memories_attempt_unique`` (migration 007) enforces uniqueness\n    # only when this is non-NULL, so legacy paths are unaffected.\n    client_request_id: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    expires_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n    deleted_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n    search_vector = mapped_column(TSVECTOR)\n\n    # RDF triple representation\n    subject_entity_id: Mapped[uuid.UUID | None] = mapped_column(\n        PG_UUID(as_uuid=True),\n        ForeignKey(\"entities.id\", ondelete=\"SET NULL\"),\n    )\n    predicate: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n    object_value: Mapped[str | None] = mapped_column(Text)\n\n    # Temporal validity windows\n    ts_valid_start: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n    ts_valid_end: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n\n    # Status lifecycle\n    status: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(\n        Text, server_default=text(\"'active'\"), nullable=False\n    )\n\n    # Visibility scope\n    visibility: Mapped[str] = mapped_column(\n        Text,\n        server_default=text(\"'scope_team'\"),\n        nullable=False,\n    )\n\n    # Recall tracking (incremented on agent-facing retrievals only)\n    recall_count: Mapped[int] = mapped_column(\n        Integer, server_default=text(\"0\"), nullable=False\n    )\n    last_recalled_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(DateTime(timezone=True))\n\n    # Crystallizer dedup tracking\n    last_dedup_checked_at: Mapped[datetime | None] = mapped_column(\n        DateTime(timezone=True)\n    )\n\n    # Contradiction tracking\n    supersedes_id: Mapped[uuid.UUID | None] = mapped_column(\n        PG_UUID(as_uuid=True),\n        ForeignKey(\"memories.id\", ondelete=\"SET NULL\"),\n    )\n\n    __table_args__ = (\n        Index(\"ix_memories_tenant_type\", \"tenant_id\", \"memory_type\"),\n        Index(\"ix_memories_tenant_agent\", \"tenant_id\", \"agent_id\"),\n        Index(\"ix_memories_content_hash\", \"tenant_id\", \"content_hash\"),\n        # Backs per-attempt bulk-write idempotency (CAURA-602). Created\n        # ``CONCURRENTLY`` in migration 007 with the same predicates;\n        # declared here so SQLAlchemy reflection / Alembic autogen\n        # round-trips match the live schema. ``COALESCE(fleet_id, '')``\n        # makes fleetless rows participate in the unique constraint —\n        # PostgreSQL treats NULLs as distinct by default, so without\n        # this two retries with ``fleet_id IS NULL`` would both insert.\n        Index(\n            \"ix_memories_attempt_unique\",\n            \"tenant_id\",\n            func.coalesce(text(\"fleet_id\"), \"\"),\n            \"client_request_id\",\n            unique=True,\n            postgresql_where=text(\n                \"deleted_at IS NULL AND client_request_id IS NOT NULL\"\n            ),\n        ),\n        Index(\"ix_memories_valid_range\", \"ts_valid_start\", \"ts_valid_end\"),\n        Index(\"ix_memories_subject_entity\", \"subject_entity_id\"),\n        Index(\"ix_memories_recall_count\", \"recall_count\"),\n        Index(\"ix_memories_tenant_fleet\", \"tenant_id\", \"fleet_id\"),\n        # Backs the cursor-paginated list path (``list_by_filters`` +\n        # the ``memclaw_list`` MCP tool) which orders by\n        # ``(created_at DESC, id DESC)`` under ``tenant_id = ?`` and\n        # ``deleted_at IS NULL``. Partial WHERE keeps the index small\n        # since soft-deleted rows are never read on the hot path.\n        # Bare-column references (``created_at.desc()`` not\n        # ``text(\"created_at DESC\")``) so Alembic autogen can reflect\n        # and compare the index — matches ``analysis_report.py:38``.\n        Index(\n            \"ix_memories_tenant_created_active\",\n            \"tenant_id\",\n            created_at.desc(),\n            id.desc(),\n            postgresql_where=text(\"deleted_at IS NULL\"),\n        ),\n        # Backs the CAURA-656 purge-fanout discovery query\n        # (``list_tenants_with_purgeable_memories``). Every other\n        # partial index on this table is keyed on\n        # ``deleted_at IS NULL`` (active path); without this\n        # complement the soft-deleted-side discovery falls back to a\n        # full scan.\n        Index(\n            \"ix_memories_purgeable\",\n            \"tenant_id\",\n            postgresql_where=text(\"deleted_at IS NOT NULL\"),\n        ),\n    )","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":136,"totalLines":136,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/models/memory.py","time":{"start":1780727723734,"end":1780727723739}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cd08191b283194355cbacb3"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6d1001IyUBjGvDqehAy3","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723742,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_DJoGtmnNJd6zaAgncVLdswRz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/schema.py","offset":88,"limit":40},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/schema.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n88:         format guidance, so downstream tag-joins see stable keys.\n89:         \"\"\"\n90:         if not isinstance(raw, list):\n91:             return []\n92:         seen: set[str] = set()\n93:         normalised: list[str] = []\n94:         for item in raw:\n95:             tag = _normalize_tag(item)\n96:             if not tag or tag in seen:\n97:                 continue\n98:             seen.add(tag)\n99:             normalised.append(tag)\n100:             if len(normalised) >= _TAGS_MAX:\n101:                 break\n102:         return normalised\n103: \n104:     ts_valid_start: str | None = None\n105:     ts_valid_end: str | None = None\n106:     contains_pii: bool = False\n107:     pii_types: list[str] = []\n108:     retrieval_hint: str = \"\"\n109:     atomic_facts: list[AtomicFact] | None = None\n110:     llm_ms: int = 0\n\n(End of file - total 110 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"        format guidance, so downstream tag-joins see stable keys.\n        \"\"\"\n        if not isinstance(raw, list):\n            return []\n        seen: set[str] = set()\n        normalised: list[str] = []\n        for item in raw:\n            tag = _normalize_tag(item)\n            if not tag or tag in seen:\n                continue\n            seen.add(tag)\n            normalised.append(tag)\n            if len(normalised) >= _TAGS_MAX:\n                break\n        return normalised\n\n    ts_valid_start: str | None = None\n    ts_valid_end: str | None = None\n    contains_pii: bool = False\n    pii_types: list[str] = []","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/schema.py","text":"        format guidance, so downstream tag-joins see stable keys.\n        \"\"\"\n        if not isinstance(raw, list):\n            return []\n        seen: set[str] = set()\n        normalised: list[str] = []\n        for item in raw:\n            tag = _normalize_tag(item)\n            if not tag or tag in seen:\n                continue\n            seen.add(tag)\n            normalised.append(tag)\n            if len(normalised) >= _TAGS_MAX:\n                break\n        return normalised\n\n    ts_valid_start: str | None = None\n    ts_valid_end: str | None = None\n    contains_pii: bool = False\n    pii_types: list[str] = []\n    retrieval_hint: str = \"\"\n    atomic_facts: list[AtomicFact] | None = None\n    llm_ms: int = 0","lineStart":88,"lineEnd":110,"totalLines":110,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/schema.py","time":{"start":1780727723737,"end":1780727723742}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cd48191b22d6bd16eff7ef7"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6d8001wGg7QMDJ23Ucv4","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727723747,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_wCsJ6GlhvyXnI1ZqEACrkozR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/integration-without-plugin.md","offset":156,"limit":80},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/integration-without-plugin.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n156: ## 4. Elevate trust (when needed)\n157: \n158: The default `trust_level=1` lets the agent write to its home fleet. Elevate when you need cross-fleet writes, keystone authoring, or deletes:\n159: \n160: ```bash\n161: curl -X PATCH \"https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/agents/quote-agent-na/trust?tenant_id=$TENANT_ID\" \\\n162:   -H \"X-API-Key: $MC_TENANT_KEY\" \\\n163:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n164:   -d '{\"trust_level\": 2}'\n165: ```\n166: \n167: Trust levels:\n168: - `0` — read-only.\n169: - `1` — write to home fleet.\n170: - `2` — cross-fleet read.\n171: - `3` — cross-fleet write + delete + update others' memories.\n172: \n173: If you provisioned with `initial_trust`, this step is already done — confirm with `/whoami`.\n174: \n175: ---\n176: \n177: ## End-to-end bootstrap, one block\n178: \n179: ```bash\n180: TENANT_KEY=mc_...   # tenant-scoped credential\n181: AGENT_ID=\"quote-agent-na\"\n182: FLEET_ID=\"na-sales\"\n183: \n184: # 1. Provision agent + Agent row + trust + fleet in one call.\n185: RESP=$(curl -s -X POST https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision \\\n186:   -H \"X-API-Key: $TENANT_KEY\" \\\n187:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n188:   -d \"{\\\"agent_id\\\":\\\"$AGENT_ID\\\",\\\"initial_trust\\\":1,\\\"initial_fleet\\\":\\\"$FLEET_ID\\\"}\")\n189: AGENT_KEY=$(echo \"$RESP\" | python3 -c \"import json,sys; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['raw_key'])\")\n190: # AGENT_KEY is an mc_… agent-scoped credential.\n191: \n192: # 2. Verify.\n193: curl -s https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/whoami -H \"X-API-Key: $AGENT_KEY\"\n194: \n195: # 3. Use.\n196: curl -s https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/memories \\\n197:   -H \"X-API-Key: $AGENT_KEY\" \\\n198:   -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n199:   -d \"{\\\"tenant_id\\\":\\\"$TENANT_ID\\\",\\\"agent_id\\\":\\\"$AGENT_ID\\\",\\\"fleet_id\\\":\\\"$FLEET_ID\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"Hello world\\\"}\"\n200: ```\n201: \n202: Four steps, one round-trip per agent. The bootstrap dance from earlier integration attempts (provision → fake-write → patch trust → seed) is no longer necessary.\n203: \n204: ---\n205: \n206: ## Idempotency\n207: \n208: A write of identical content (same `agent_id`, same `fleet_id`) is retry-safe via MCP:\n209: \n210: - First call → `201` with the new memory id.\n211: - Identical retry → `200` with `{ \"status\": \"duplicate\", \"existing_id\": \"…\" }`.\n212: \n213: Cross-agent writes of identical content no longer collide — each agent gets its own record.\n214: \n215: ---\n216: \n217: ## Common pitfalls\n218: \n219: - **`POST /provision` returns the raw key once.** Save it before the response goes out of scope.\n220: - **`PATCH /agents/{id}/trust` returns 404 immediately after provisioning.** This should not happen post-2026-05-13; if it does, the Agent row was not materialized atomically. Check `whoami` and `GET /api/v1/agents/{id}`.\n221: - **`/mcp` returns 401 with an `Authorization: Bearer mc_…` (or legacy `mca_…`) header but works with `X-API-Key`.** Make sure you're hitting a memclaw build dated 2026-05-13 or later — earlier builds rejected non-JWT bearer tokens.\n222: - **Streaming client hangs on initialize.** If hitting `/mcp` (no slash) caused a hang on older builds, append the trailing slash or upgrade — current builds serve both paths without redirect.\n223: \n224: ---\n225: \n226: ## Reference\n227: \n228: - `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` — atomic provisioning (this guide).\n229: - `GET /api/v1/whoami` — identity probe.\n230: - `GET /api/v1/agents/{id}?tenant_id=...` — agent detail.\n231: - `PATCH /api/v1/agents/{id}/trust?tenant_id=...` — change trust level.\n232: - `POST /api/v1/memories` — REST write (mirrors `memclaw_write` over MCP).\n233: - `mcp://…/mcp/` — streamable-http MCP endpoint.\n\n(End of file - total 233 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"## 4. Elevate trust (when needed)\n\nThe default `trust_level=1` lets the agent write to its home fleet. Elevate when you need cross-fleet writes, keystone authoring, or deletes:\n\n```bash\ncurl -X PATCH \"https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/agents/quote-agent-na/trust?tenant_id=$TENANT_ID\" \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: $MC_TENANT_KEY\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"trust_level\": 2}'\n```\n\nTrust levels:\n- `0` — read-only.\n- `1` — write to home fleet.\n- `2` — cross-fleet read.\n- `3` — cross-fleet write + delete + update others' memories.\n\nIf you provisioned with `initial_trust`, this step is already done — confirm with `/whoami`.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/integration-without-plugin.md","text":"## 4. Elevate trust (when needed)\n\nThe default `trust_level=1` lets the agent write to its home fleet. Elevate when you need cross-fleet writes, keystone authoring, or deletes:\n\n```bash\ncurl -X PATCH \"https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/agents/quote-agent-na/trust?tenant_id=$TENANT_ID\" \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: $MC_TENANT_KEY\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\"trust_level\": 2}'\n```\n\nTrust levels:\n- `0` — read-only.\n- `1` — write to home fleet.\n- `2` — cross-fleet read.\n- `3` — cross-fleet write + delete + update others' memories.\n\nIf you provisioned with `initial_trust`, this step is already done — confirm with `/whoami`.\n\n---\n\n## End-to-end bootstrap, one block\n\n```bash\nTENANT_KEY=mc_...   # tenant-scoped credential\nAGENT_ID=\"quote-agent-na\"\nFLEET_ID=\"na-sales\"\n\n# 1. Provision agent + Agent row + trust + fleet in one call.\nRESP=$(curl -s -X POST https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: $TENANT_KEY\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d \"{\\\"agent_id\\\":\\\"$AGENT_ID\\\",\\\"initial_trust\\\":1,\\\"initial_fleet\\\":\\\"$FLEET_ID\\\"}\")\nAGENT_KEY=$(echo \"$RESP\" | python3 -c \"import json,sys; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['raw_key'])\")\n# AGENT_KEY is an mc_… agent-scoped credential.\n\n# 2. Verify.\ncurl -s https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/whoami -H \"X-API-Key: $AGENT_KEY\"\n\n# 3. Use.\ncurl -s https://memclaw.dev/api/v1/memories \\\n  -H \"X-API-Key: $AGENT_KEY\" \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d \"{\\\"tenant_id\\\":\\\"$TENANT_ID\\\",\\\"agent_id\\\":\\\"$AGENT_ID\\\",\\\"fleet_id\\\":\\\"$FLEET_ID\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"Hello world\\\"}\"\n```\n\nFour steps, one round-trip per agent. The bootstrap dance from earlier integration attempts (provision → fake-write → patch trust → seed) is no longer necessary.\n\n---\n\n## Idempotency\n\nA write of identical content (same `agent_id`, same `fleet_id`) is retry-safe via MCP:\n\n- First call → `201` with the new memory id.\n- Identical retry → `200` with `{ \"status\": \"duplicate\", \"existing_id\": \"…\" }`.\n\nCross-agent writes of identical content no longer collide — each agent gets its own record.\n\n---\n\n## Common pitfalls\n\n- **`POST /provision` returns the raw key once.** Save it before the response goes out of scope.\n- **`PATCH /agents/{id}/trust` returns 404 immediately after provisioning.** This should not happen post-2026-05-13; if it does, the Agent row was not materialized atomically. Check `whoami` and `GET /api/v1/agents/{id}`.\n- **`/mcp` returns 401 with an `Authorization: Bearer mc_…` (or legacy `mca_…`) header but works with `X-API-Key`.** Make sure you're hitting a memclaw build dated 2026-05-13 or later — earlier builds rejected non-JWT bearer tokens.\n- **Streaming client hangs on initialize.** If hitting `/mcp` (no slash) caused a hang on older builds, append the trailing slash or upgrade — current builds serve both paths without redirect.\n\n---\n\n## Reference\n\n- `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` — atomic provisioning (this guide).\n- `GET /api/v1/whoami` — identity probe.\n- `GET /api/v1/agents/{id}?tenant_id=...` — agent detail.\n- `PATCH /api/v1/agents/{id}/trust?tenant_id=...` — change trust level.\n- `POST /api/v1/memories` — REST write (mirrors `memclaw_write` over MCP).\n- `mcp://…/mcp/` — streamable-http MCP endpoint.","lineStart":156,"lineEnd":233,"totalLines":233,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/integration-without-plugin.md","time":{"start":1780727723740,"end":1780727723746}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c3bec3d6501bffc016a23bfab9cd88191bf56996d2de66621"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4b6da001o09OSttYv6g8vc","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba475e2001k3nSzMScTeiewj"}}
