{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727811173,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_UtfbFHxrnJoo5pC5MknMsag2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/constants.py","offset":535,"limit":16},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/constants.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n535:     },\n536: }\n537: \n538: # ── Agent trust levels ──\n539: TRUST_LEVELS = {\n540:     0: \"restricted\",\n541:     1: \"standard\",\n542:     2: \"cross_fleet\",\n543:     3: \"admin\",\n544: }\n545: DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL = 1\n546: MIN_TRUST_LEVEL = 0\n547: MAX_TRUST_LEVEL = 3\n548: \n549: # ── Auth ──\n550: API_KEY_HEADER = \"X-API-Key\"\n\n(Showing lines 535-550 of 638. Use offset=551 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"    },\n}\n\n# ── Agent trust levels ──\nTRUST_LEVELS = {\n    0: \"restricted\",\n    1: \"standard\",\n    2: \"cross_fleet\",\n    3: \"admin\",\n}\nDEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL = 1\nMIN_TRUST_LEVEL = 0\nMAX_TRUST_LEVEL = 3\n\n# ── Auth ──\nAPI_KEY_HEADER = \"X-API-Key\"","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/constants.py","text":"    },\n}\n\n# ── Agent trust levels ──\nTRUST_LEVELS = {\n    0: \"restricted\",\n    1: \"standard\",\n    2: \"cross_fleet\",\n    3: \"admin\",\n}\nDEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL = 1\nMIN_TRUST_LEVEL = 0\nMAX_TRUST_LEVEL = 3\n\n# ── Auth ──\nAPI_KEY_HEADER = \"X-API-Key\"","lineStart":535,"lineEnd":550,"totalLines":638,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/constants.py","time":{"start":1780727811168,"end":1780727811172}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07e886c2c7289856016a23c001b0788191a75f79d0b90747d9"}},"id":"prt_e9ba606a7001rzx41yi6ntOdwa","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","messageID":"msg_e9ba5f809001oF97TISa5FC70Y"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780727811477,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba60d93001LjIZA3AnEy0rM2","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"62021fd28fb5987f90e3f3a282227b0d6928d936","messageID":"msg_e9ba5f809001oF97TISa5FC70Y","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":124673,"input":693,"output":76,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":0,"read":123904}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780727813552,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba615ae001B93RpHj5wWxSJg","messageID":"msg_e9ba60ed4001UhmSrVREV53Toz","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","snapshot":"4433d1b6f76c0d41259b05cb28b52e5c2741cb12","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780727902817,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba648cb001WjfUBscWbdas7X","messageID":"msg_e9ba60ed4001UhmSrVREV53Toz","sessionID":"ses_1645cad25ffe4Zj0121cwP5hrZ","type":"text","text":"## Mechanism\nMemClaw’s governance is built for fleet deployment, not a personal local store. The public contract states the product is “multi-tenant, multi-agent” and “built for fleets, not single agents,” with scoped memory, cross-agent propagation, and fleet-wide trust tiers as core architecture (`README.md:30`, `README.md:36`).\n\nScope model: every memory row has `tenant_id`, optional `fleet_id`, `agent_id`, and `visibility`; visibility defaults to `scope_team` (`common/models/memory.py:19`, `common/models/memory.py:20`, `common/models/memory.py:21`, `common/models/memory.py:61`, `common/models/memory.py:64`). Constants define the three visibility scopes: `scope_agent`, `scope_team`, `scope_org` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:97`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:105`). The agent-facing skill states the write-time meanings: `scope_agent` private, `scope_team` default fleet, `scope_org` all fleets in tenant (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:67`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`).\n\nTenant and cross-tenant enforcement: auth stores the current tenant and optional readable tenants in context vars, then sets Postgres GUCs `app.tenant_id` and `app.readable_tenant_ids` for RLS-aware deployments (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:33`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:74`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:79`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`). MCP auth similarly resolves `X-Tenant-ID`, verified `X-Agent-ID`, readable tenants, and capabilities into request context (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:145`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:165`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:206`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:213`).\n\nRead filtering is default-deny for private agent memories: list/search returns `scope_org` and `scope_team`, plus `scope_agent` only when the caller owns it; otherwise `scope_agent` is excluded (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:114`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:140`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). Search applies the same visibility filter and fleet filter, with `scope_org` allowed to escape explicit fleet scoping (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:445`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:450`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:454`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:459`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:465`).\n\nTrust tiers: MemClaw has four agent trust levels: `restricted`, `standard`, `cross_fleet`, `admin`, defaulting to `1` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:538`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:539`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:545`). The public guide maps them to capabilities: `0` read-only, `1` home-fleet write, `2` cross-fleet read, `3` cross-fleet write/delete/update-others (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:168`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:169`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:170`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`). Service gates enforce this: cross-fleet write requires trust >=3, cross-fleet read requires trust >=2, delete requires trust >=3, and by-id access reuses `scope_agent` ownership plus fleet trust ladder (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:149`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:185`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:201`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:204`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:250`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). MCP recall narrows low-trust agents without explicit fleet filters back to their own fleet, then applies `enforce_fleet_read` for explicit fleet reads (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:512`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:516`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:521`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:523`).\n\nSuppression: enterprise org soft-delete emits `memclaw.org.suppression-changed`; the event carries tenant IDs plus action `suppress` or `restore` (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:1`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:40`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:41`). The handler writes each affected tenant into a suppression mirror and re-raises partial failures so Pub/Sub redelivers rather than leaving an authz hole (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:14`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:15`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:85`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`). Core API checks suppression on authenticated requests and returns 403 with a generic suspended message (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:283`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). The suppression cache intentionally fails open on storage errors to avoid self-DOS (`core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:118`).\n\nPII quarantine: the README claims PII is “auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries” (`README.md:253`). In the capped code pass, I found the detection and metadata/reporting surface: enrichment schema has `contains_pii` and `pii_types` (`common/enrichment/schema.py:106`, `common/enrichment/schema.py:107`), memory creation writes those into metadata (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:631`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:634`), and stats count PII-tagged memories (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:924`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). I did not see quarantine enforcement code in the files read.\n\nAudit logging: MemClaw has a generic `audit_log` model with `tenant_id`, optional `agent_id`, `action`, `resource_type`, `resource_id`, JSON detail, and timestamp (`common/models/audit.py:11`, `common/models/audit.py:17`, `common/models/audit.py:18`, `common/models/audit.py:19`, `common/models/audit.py:20`, `common/models/audit.py:22`, `common/models/audit.py:23`). `log_action` builds the audit payload and queues it when the audit queue is active (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:32`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:58`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:63`). Cross-tenant reads emit one audit event per source tenant, logged to the source tenant for forensic visibility (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:71`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:84`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:103`). Settings have a separate append-only per-change audit trail with `changed_by` and flat diffs (`common/models/organization_settings.py:36`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:37`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:49`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:51`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`).\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory\n1. **Claim** · ADAPT trust tiers into provenance trust, not access-control trust. **Evidence** · MemClaw trust levels gate fleet powers (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`) and enforcement lives in fleet read/write/delete gates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `provenance-trust-weighting-for-derived-memory`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-importing authz semantics would add fake multi-agent complexity to a single-user store. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The transferable concept is “not all memories deserve equal authority.” Spec Kit already has importance tiers and constitutional always-surface memories; the missing analog is trust weighting for source/provenance, e.g. human-authored > validated automated > shadow-derived > stale/low-confidence.\n\n2. **Claim** · ADAPT append-only audit for automated memory mutations. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s settings path writes a flat diff audit row after updates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`), and generic audit events include tenant, agent, action, resource, and detail (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:56`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `automated-mutation-audit-trail`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full fleet audit queue is unnecessary and can become operational noise. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user Spec Kit does not need forensic tenant accounting, but it does need explainability for self-maintaining index changes, shadow feedback promotions, tier changes, bulk deletes, retention sweeps, and causal-edge backfills.\n\n3. **Claim** · REJECT agent/fleet/cross-tenant scope machinery; keep only a local default-deny analog for sensitive auto-derived state. **Evidence** · MemClaw scopes are explicitly fleet concepts (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:72`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:73`), and query filters prevent `scope_agent` leaks across callers (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). **Maps-to** · 027 child or new sub-packet: `local-visibility-for-ephemeral-derived-state`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · If copied directly, Spec Kit would gain meaningless “agents/fleets” and confuse retrieval policy. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · There is no cross-team leak risk in a local single-user database. The only useful analog is default-deny surfacing for draft, shadow, quarantined, or low-confidence derived memories until promoted.\n\n4. **Claim** · DEFER PII quarantine; adopt only lightweight sensitive-content tagging if there is a concrete local need. **Evidence** · README claims PII quarantine before crossing fleet boundaries (`README.md:253`), while visible code in this pass shows PII detection metadata and counts (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet if pursued: `local-sensitive-memory-tagging`. **Verdict** · DEFER. **Risk** · PII quarantine can become false-positive friction in a personal/local store; it solves cross-fleet exposure, which Spec Kit lacks. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The concept of marking sensitive generated memories may transfer for operator awareness or export hygiene, but quarantine-as-is is a fleet boundary mechanism.\n\n5. **Claim** · REJECT suppression as org lifecycle enforcement; ADAPT “suppression” only as a local disabled/archived memory state. **Evidence** · Suppression mirrors enterprise soft-delete events into tenant rows (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`) and blocks authenticated requests for suppressed tenants (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). **Maps-to** · existing Spec Kit retention/archive surfaces or new sub-packet: `memory-suppression-state-for-retrieval`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · Importing tenant suppression would create dead configuration and fake security posture. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · A single-user local store needs no org soft-delete boundary. It may benefit from explicit suppression flags for “do not retrieve this memory” without deleting evidence.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nMulti-tenant RLS context, `tenant_id` GUCs, and readable-tenant GUCs do not transfer directly; they exist to isolate tenants and widen reads only for authorized cross-tenant credentials (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`).\n\nAgent-scoped credentials, gateway-injected `X-Agent-ID`, `X-Readable-Tenant-IDs`, `X-Capabilities`, and gateway shared-secret perimeter checks are fleet ingress machinery, not local-memory needs (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:210`; `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:385`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:395`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:401`).\n\nFleet read/write ladders should not be ported as authorization. Trust >=2 for cross-fleet read and trust >=3 for cross-fleet write/delete are meaningful only when multiple fleets and agents share a tenant (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`).\n\nPer-tenant concurrency bulkheads and rate limiting are noisy-neighbor controls. Spec Kit’s local SQLite/vector store has different bottlenecks and no tenant starvation problem (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:1`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:4`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:150`; `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/rate_limit.py:8`).\n\nOrg suppression eventing, tenant-suppression mirrors, Pub/Sub redelivery, DLQ behavior, and fail-open suppression cache are enterprise lifecycle controls. They do not map to a single-user local memory system except as a simple retrieval-suppressed state (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`; `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`).\n\nCross-tenant read audit should not transfer as-is. Spec Kit can audit automated changes, but it does not need “who read from my tenant” forensic rows (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:84`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:99`).\n\nPII quarantine before cross-fleet exposure is mostly negative knowledge for Spec Kit. If local export/sync features later appear, sensitive tagging may become relevant; until then, quarantine is solving a fleet leak boundary (`README.md:253`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`).\n\n## Open questions\n1. Where, if anywhere, is MemClaw’s README-claimed PII quarantine enforced beyond metadata tagging and stats?\n2. Does Spec Kit already record enough audit metadata for `memory_bulk_delete`, `memory_save`, `retention_sweep`, causal backfill, embedding reconcile, and tier updates?\n3. Should Spec Kit distinguish `source_trust` from `importance_tier`, so “constitutional” importance cannot be confused with “human-verified” provenance?\n4. Should shadow-first feedback reducers write an audit/event log before promotion, or is current telemetry sufficient?\n5. Is a local `suppressed` or `do_not_surface` retrieval state needed, or do existing `deprecated`, `temporary`, and archive states cover it?\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"083\",\"focus\":\"governance / trust tiers / scoping / audit\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.68,\"topVerdicts\":[\"REJECT: fleet-scale tenant/fleet/cross-tenant scoping and suppression machinery\",\"ADAPT: provenance trust weighting and append-only audit for automated memory mutations\"],\"sources\":[\"README.md:253\",\"common/models/memory.py:61\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846\"]}","time":{"start":1780727826635,"end":1780727902813},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0fd2795690053e97016a23c01299808191820e53c16adc9046","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
